THE CRISSCROSS SHADOW\par
\par
\par
CHAPTER I\line\b\i A Strange Sale\par
\b0\i0\par
\i "\i0 I\i  \i0 WANT to speak to my nephews Frank and Joe Hardy at once," said an excited voice on the telephone. "It's urgent."\par
"Yes, Miss Hardy," replied the manager of Bay-port High's football team. "They're out on the field. I'll get 'em."\par
Meanwhile, on the thirty-yard line Coach Devlin was saying, "Okay, team. Let's run through our defensive play once more."\par
The eleven lined up-the regulars on defense, the scrubs facing them.\par
"86X," barked Frank Hardy, captain and quarterback, as the opposing center moved over the pigskin.\par
The ball was snapped. At the same instant, stocky Chet Morton, the regulars' stalwart center, pulled out of the line to cover the left flank. The scrubs' halfback darted up and over the line of scrimmage.\par
"Tackle him, Chet, tackle him!" shouted Frank.\par
Chet plowed into the second-string ball carrier and brought him to the ground for no gain.\par
"Good going, boys," said Coach Devlin. "I think you've got that defensive play down pretty well. Once around the field and then into the showers," he said, dismissing them.\par
Frank and his brother Joe, a year younger, jogged along together. Lithe, blond-haired Joe, who played left halfback, was puffing.\par
"Coach really had us working on that 86X, didn't he?"\par
"I'll say he did," tall, dark-haired Frank replied. "But it's going to come in mighty handy when we play Hopkinsville-"\par
"Frank! Joe!" the manager called out. "Telephone call for you. Better hurry. Your aunt seems very excited!"\par
The brothers looked at each other wonderingly. Sons of Fenton Hardy, the famous detective, they were accomplished sleuths in spite of their youth. They had often received urgent calls but never in a locker room!\par
Joe hurried to the phone. "Hello," he said anxiously.\par
"Joe, is that you?" asked a crisp feminine voice. "This is Aunt Gertrude."\par
"What's up?"\par
Aunt Gertrude, who was staying at the Hardy home, was the boys' favorite relative. Though she did not hesitate on occasion to reprimand her nephews, they had great respect for her insight into human nature.\par
"There's a strange salesman in the house," Aunt Gertrude reported. "He's trying to sell your mother some leather goods, but I don't like his looks. I'm sure he's a swindler. I've seen his picture somewhere in the papers."\par
Joe whistled softly. "We'll come right home, Auntie," he promised.\par
The boys did not wait to shower or change their clothes, but hurried to their convertible.\par
Since their father was in San Francisco on a secret mission-so secret that he had not even told the boys its nature-Frank and Joe felt a protective responsibility toward the two women at home.\par
As he maneuvered the sleek car through Bay-port's busy streets, Frank looked puzzled.\par
"I don't like this at all, Joe," he said.\par
"Let's take a look through the window before we go in," Joe suggested. "You know what Dad says. A little undercover sleuthing in advance is better than barging in head-on."\par
"Good idea."\par
When they reached the tree-lined neighborhood where the Hardy home was located, Frank proceeded cautiously.\par
"We'll park here," he said, quietly turning off the motor and gliding to the curb about three hundred feet from the house.\par
The boys went up a neighbor's driveway, crossed the back yard, and approached their own house from the rear.\par
"How about looking in the side living-room window?" Frank whispered. Joe nodded.\par
The boys flattened themselves against the side of the house below the window. Cautiously they lifted their heads until their eyes were on a level with the sill. A strange man, his back to them, was there alone.\par
Suddenly Joe gave a start and said, "He just took something off Mother's desk!"\par
"What is it?" Frank asked. "I can't make it out-oh, yes-it's Dad's key case!"\par
As the youthful detectives watched, the man, unaware that he was being observed, opened the case and quickly slipped a key off one of the rings.\par
The boys did not wait to see any more. They dashed around the house, unlocked the front door, and ran into the hall.\par
"Why, hello, boys," a pleasant feminine voice said. Mrs. Hardy was descending the stairway. "What brings you home so early from practice- and in your football uniforms?"\par
"Hello, Mother!" they answered together as they followed her into the living room.\par
Joe burst out, "This man is what brings us here."\par
"I don't understand," she replied as the stranger stared at them with an air of surprise.\par
"Why did you pick up my father's key case and take a key from it?" Frank asked sharply.\par
"What do you mean?" the stranger demanded angrily.\par
"Frank! Joe!" their mother exclaimed, taken aback by her sons' actions. "You'd better apologize to Mr. Breck. I bought a new key case from him for your father."\par
"And I was merely transferring the old ones to the new case while your mother went upstairs for her pocketbook," Mr. Breck said triumphantly.\par
Embarrassed, the boys looked at the two cases. There were three keys in the new one.\par
"Here is a letter of introduction that Mr. Breck brought from Mrs. Wilson," their mother quickly explained as she handed them a folded sheet of paper.\par
Her sons scanned the typewritten letter, which told what a reliable man Mr. Breck was and how reasonably he was selling fine handmade leather articles. At the bottom of the page was a signature which the boys recognized as that of an old friend of their mother and father.\par
As they looked up, Mr. Breck gazed straight at the boys. A taunting smile outlined the lips of the dark, burly man who was about thirty-five years old.\par
"No reason to get excited," he said smoothly. "I've just been showing your mother some beautiful hand-tooled leather-"\par
Breck stopped speaking and looked flustered when he saw Miss Hardy in the doorway. Tall, stern Aunt Gertrude stood there glaring in unfriendly fashion. But the salesman recovered himself quickly.\par
"Oh another customer," he said.\par
"Indeed not," stated the boys' aunt firmly. "Laura," she addressed her sister-in-law, "are you sure this man is-?"\par
"Oh, please," Mrs. Hardy begged, greatly distressed.\par
Meanwhile, Joe had been silently counting the keys. He did this twice to make certain how many were there. He knew the exact number there should be because Mr. Hardy, shortly before he left, had given the keys to his wife in Joe's presence. The boy's sleuthing instinct had prompted him to count them at that time. Now one key was missing!\par
"Mr. Breck," he demanded, his eyes flashing, "what did you do with a thin brass key that was in this old case?"\par
"Why . . . why . . ." the stranger stammered, hunting for words. "How dare you accuse me of stealing!"\par
"There's a key missing-a special one. Hand it over!" Joe insisted.\par
"I haven't got it, you young whippersnapper," the man replied indignantly.\par
"Please!" Mrs. Hardy interrupted. "Mr. Hardy, no doubt, removed the key himself."\par
"I'm not going to stay here and be insulted any longer!" Breck exclaimed in anger.\par
He moved to his small suitcase, tossed his samples inside, and snapped it shut.\par
"I'm getting out of this house," he said hotly. "I've had enough of your insinuations."\par
Joe made a move to detain the salesman. But his mother forbade it.\par
"Let him go, Joe," she advised. "No key is worth such a scene."\par
"But, Mother, it's the one to the file in Dad's study-"\par
"We still don't know that your father didn't take it."\par
The boys were reluctant to let the man go, but their mother's word was law. Breck then stalked out, slamming the front door behind him.\par
Mrs. Hardy, still looking distressed, commented:\par
"I know you don't trust the man, Frank and Joe. But I did hate to have a scene, especially since there was no proof against him."\par
"Sure, Mother, I understand," Frank answered. "Though the way he acted was mighty suspicious."\par
"I'll say," Joe agreed. "He'd better not show his face around here again."\par
The boys went upstairs, removed their football gear, and showered.\par
Five minutes later, while they were dressing, they heard Aunt Gertrude cry out. As the boys were speculating about what had happened, she knocked on their door.\par
"Hurry up! Go find that man Breck. He's stolen your father's picture!"\par
Pulling on sweaters, they opened the door and followed her downstairs. Mrs. Hardy was staring at the top of the baby grand piano where her husband's photograph had stood for nearly a year.\par
"I guess you were right after all about that salesman," she said. "He's taken Dad's picture. But why?"\par
"We'll find out!" Frank cried.\par
They raced from the house and down the street to their car. They had little hope of locating Breck, but to their relief Joe spotted him in the center of town walking hurriedly along the sidewalk.\par
The convertible pulled up even with him. As it came to a stop, he glanced at the boys, then started to run.\par
Leaping from the car, Frank and Joe gave chase. But Breck had a head start. He turned the corner. When the Hardys reached it, the man was not in sight!\par
\par
\par
CHAPTER II\line\b\i A Clever Alibi\par
\par
\b0\i0 "WHERE'D Breck go?" Joe cried, dismayed that their quarry had eluded them.\par
He and Frank glanced at both sides of the deserted street, seeing nothing but a few parked cars.\par
Suddenly Joe cried out. "Look, between those two parked cars. Isn't that a suitcase? And a man? Come on, Frank."\par
The boys dashed across the street. Joe approached the space between the cars from the sidewalk, Frank from the street.\par
"There he is! Grab him, Joe!" Frank exclaimed as Breck tried to make a getaway.\par
Joe, executing a perfect tackle, stopped the man dead in his tracks. Grunting and panting, Breck tried to shake him off, but Frank, coming up from behind, pinned the husky salesman's shoulders to the ground, while his brother clung grimly to his legs.\par
"Get off!" Breck cried, struggling to rise.\par
"Not until we've searched you," replied Frank, holding him even more tightly.\par
Just then Joe caught sight of a policeman sauntering along on the other side of the street.\par
"Hey, Casey!" he shouted to the officer, whom they had known for years. "We can use some help!"\par
Seeing the boys and their struggling captive, Casey broke into a run.\par
"What's up, fellows?" he cried as he reached them.\par
Frank and Joe released their grip on Breck, who now made no effort to break away.\par
"This man stole a picture of my father and the key to his file cabinet," Frank replied, pointing to Breck, who glowered at the boys.\par
"Yes, we want him searched," Joe chimed in.\par
"All right," the officer's voice was stern. "Come along to headquarters, mister."\par
"Our car's around the corner," Frank said.\par
Breck started to object, but the policeman silenced him with a gesture.\par
"I never question Frank and Joe's judgment," he stated as they walked to the boys' convertible. "I guess you don't know that they're sons of the famous detective Fenton Hardy. And they're right smart detectives themselves. Solved lots of cases, like \i The Tower Treasure. \i0 And not long ago they went out West and tangled with some bad characters in \i The Secret of Wildcat Swamp"\i0\par
At police headquarters the group was met by Chief Ezra Collig, grizzled veteran of many a battle with Bayport's criminal elements. He and the Hardys had often worked together in rounding up underworld characters.\par
"Well, now, who's this man, boys?" the chief asked briskly. "What's he been up to?"\par
The Hardys quickly explained the mysterious activities of Breck.\par
"We can prove it, too!" Joe exclaimed, referring to the thefts of the picture and key. "All you've got to do is search him."\par
"No, you don't," Breck protested. "I insist upon calling my lawyer. You've got to permit that. I know my rights," he added threateningly.\par
"Okay," the officer agreed. "Who's your lawyer?"\par
"Miles Kamp," Breck replied quickly.\par
"Miles Kamp, eh? I've never heard of him. Must be a stranger to Bayport."\par
Frank and Joe looked at Breck suspiciously as the man dialed the phone on the chief's desk. After a few guarded words to Kamp, he hung up, a look of satisfaction on his face.\par
Ten minutes later Miles Kamp strode into the chief's office. He was a short, heavy-jowled man with a wide thin-lipped mouth that suggested a nasty streak in his character. He peered at them nearsightedly through thick-lensed glasses.\par
Frank turned to Joe. "I don't like his looks, do you?" he whispered as the salesman shook hands with the lawyer.\par
"No," the younger Hardy replied. "He looks even more suspicious than Breck."\par
"Now, what's going on here?" the lawyer said in an annoyed voice. "Why are you holding my client?"\par
"Calm down, Mr. Kamp," Chief Collig said to him sternly. "Mr. Breck is accused of stealing a key and a photograph belonging to Fenton Hardy. These are his sons, and they want this man searched."\par
"Searched? Why, certainly, my client will gladly agree to this," Kamp replied pompously. "Mr. Breck," he said, turning to the leather-goods salesman whose face wore a smug look, "I advise you to let the police search you. We know you have nothing to fear."\par
At Chief Collig's order the policeman went to work. He turned Breck's pockets inside out and made him remove his shoes. Then he looked through the man's suitcase.\par
"Nothing suspicious here, boys," he reported.\par
Frank's eyes were intent on a bulge under the man's shirt. "What are you hiding there?" he asked.\par
The policeman investigated and found a framed photograph of Fenton Hardy.\par
"What was the idea of taking that?" Joe said accusingly.\par
Breck's face began to redden. "Well . . . well, you see ..." the salesman stammered in embarrassment. "You're right. I \i did \i0 take your father's picture, and I apologize," he confessed sheepishly. "But I can explain."\par
"You'd better have a good reason," the chief interrupted.\par
"You see, I've always been a great admirer of Fenton Hardy," Breck went on rapidly, "and I've followed his exploits for years. So today, when I saw his picture on the piano, I couldn't resist picking it up as a souvenir."\par
"Well, that puts things in a somewhat different light," said Chief Collig.\par
"I knew you'd understand," Breck continued hastily. "And I hope the boys do. I'd like to keep the photo. It would mean a lot to me." There was a note of sincerity in his voice.\par
"I don't know," Joe replied slowly, looking at his brother questioningly.\par
"Please let me have it," Breck pleaded. "I'll give you back the frame. All I want is the photograph of Mr. Hardy."\par
"Humph-" Chief Collig began, as all looked to him for advice. "The picture isn't autographed, is it?" he asked, scanning the photograph.\par
"No."\par
"Well," the officer continued soberly, "as long as it's not signed, and since Fenton Hardy's picture has appeared so frequently in newspapers anyway, I don't see what harm there'd be if this man keeps it. Since Mr. Breck didn't take the key, we have no special charge to hold him. But it's up to you boys to decide, of course," he concluded.\par
Breck turned to Frank and Joe, a hopeful expression on his face. There were several moments of silence, during which Miles Kamp pulled out a handkerchief and made a great show of polishing his glasses. All eyes turned to the Hardys.\par
The boys looked at each other again. Years of working closely together had given each one the uncanny ability to know at a glance what the other was thinking.\par
Frank spoke. "I guess it's all right for him to keep the picture, as long as he's such a great admirer of Dad."\par
"All right. He can have it," Joe agreed. "I don't think Mother would mind."\par
"Thank you, thank you. I can't tell you how happy this makes me. It's very generous of you," Breck said effusively.\par
He moved impulsively to grasp the hands of the Hardy boys to show his gratitude. Frank and Joe acknowledged his thanks coolly, their dislike of the man by no means lessened.\par
"Well, Chief Collig," Kamp interrupted in his pompous voice, "are you satisfied that my client has done nothing wrong? If so, I suggest you release him immediately."\par
"All right, you can go," the officer replied. Then he added sternly, eyeing the salesman with disfavor, "But I'm warning you, Breck, in the future you'd better not be helping yourself to pictures in people's houses."\par
"Thank you, Chief Collig," Kamp said unctuously. "We appreciate your cooperation. Good day, boys."\par
With a bow he strutted from the room, Breck at his heels.\par
"Breck won this round," remarked Frank. "But I still don't put any stock in his explanations."\par
"I know what you mean," agreed Collig. "We don't have a thing to hold him on, though."\par
A little while later, driving home in the convertible, Joe turned to Frank.\par
"Did you notice the back of Breck's hand as he was packing his suitcase?" he asked.\par
"Yes," Frank replied. "He had a strange-looking scar on the back of it in the shape of a W. You couldn't miss it."\par
"If he were a thief, it sure would be easy to spot him," Joe replied. "By the way, remember what Aunt Gertrude said about having seen his picture somewhere identifying him as a criminal?"\par
"That's right. We'll have to check with her on that."\par
Reaching home, the boys hurried up the steps. They were famished and were looking forward to a delicious steak dinner.\par
"Hope Aunt Gertrude has apple pie to go with it." Joe grinned, anticipating the tasty meal that had been promised.\par
"I could eat at least two helpings," declared Frank as they entered the hall.\par
There they found Aunt Gertrude, greatly agitated. She was waiting for them.\par
"Joe! Frank! I was right about that so-called salesman all the time!"\par
"You mean about having seen his picture somewhere?" Frank asked.\par
"No, not that. But I just called Mrs. Wilson, the one whose name was on the reference Breck showed us."\par
"Yes?"\par
"Just as I suspected," their aunt said triumphantly. "Mrs. Wilson said that she never heard of the man in her life. That reference was forged!"\par
\par
\par
CHAPTER III\line\b\i A Dangerous Visit\par
\i0\par
\b0 "WHAT!" Frank cried out. "Mrs. Wilson never heard of Breck?"\par
Aunt Gertrude shook her head.\par
"Then he forged the signature," Joe added. "Well, we sure were taken in. That guy probably had the key all the time-in his mouth maybe."\par
"And slipped it to Kamp. Joe, how could we be so dumb?"\par
"Anyway, we can try to find him. I want to question him further."\par
"Not until we get a new lock for Dad's file," Frank said emphatically. "After going through all that trouble to get the key, Breck might try to use it!"\par
The boys excused themselves and hurried to a trusted locksmith with whom their father dealt. He supplied them with a new lock and instructed them how to install it.\par
After Frank and Joe had arrived home and had just replaced the old lock, a voice behind them said:\par
"Neat job, fellows!"\par
The boys whirled. "Sam Radley!" they exclaimed, and hurried across the room to greet their visitor.\par
Radley was Fenton Hardy's able assistant, and the boys knew him well because he had helped them solve many tough problems. They had not seen him in several weeks and knew that he had been on the top-secret assignment with their father. They hoped he had news of Mr. Hardy.\par
"You'll stay for dinner, Sam?" Mrs. Hardy invited, coming into the room. "That will give us a chance to hear about your case."\par
"Thank you. I'd like to."\par
"How's Dad?" Joe asked after they sat down.\par
Sam smiled. "Your father's fine."\par
"What's the case about?" Frank put in. "Or can't you tell us?"\par
"Just a little," the detective replied, choosing his words carefully. "Your dad and I are working for the government. There have been several cases of sabotage in important industries throughout the country.\par
"It looks as though these cases are part of some master plan. We think the same gang is involved in all of them, but so far we haven't been able to find any clues that point to the guilty persons.\par
That's about all I can tell you," Sam concluded.\par
Frank gave a long, low whistle. "Sounds like an important - and dangerous - case."\par
"We're working on a mystery of our own," put in Joe.\par
Briefly the boys recounted the events of the past few hours, ending with Aunt Gertrude's report of the forged letter of reference.\par
"That man Breck!" their aunt exclaimed. "I just know I've seen his picture in connection with something dishonest. Land sakes, I've been around detectives long enough to know a suspicious character when I see one!"\par
"You're better at it than I am," Mrs. Hardy remarked ruefully. "But then, you're Fenton's sister."\par
"And just the person to help us find Breck," Frank said. "We'll go to police headquarters in the morning and look at their rogues' gallery."\par
Right after breakfast the next day the boys drove her downtown. She marched purposefully into headquarters, followed by her nephews. It was obvious that Aunt Gertrude meant to find out where she had seen the thief's picture. The boys knew that it was wise to keep in the background when she was in that mood.\par
"Good morning, Chief," she greeted Collig as the trio was ushered into his office.\par
"Aunt Gertrude wants to look at your mug file to see if she can identify Breck," Frank informed the officer.\par
"Well, well, so they're making a detective out of you, too," he joked, showing Aunt Gertrude several albums of pictures which lay on a table.\par
Miss Hardy leafed through the pages slowly. Suddenly she gave a start. "That looks as if it might be Breck," she said excitedly.\par
"It might be," replied Joe, peering over her shoulder, "except that it's Jerry 'the Character' Slocomb, and he's now serving time in the federal penitentiary for counterfeiting."\par
"Gracious sakes," responded Aunt Gertrude. "Well, what about him?" she asked, pointing to another photograph. "He certainly looks like Breck."\par
"Yes, he does," admitted Frank, "but that man was picked up a couple of days ago on the West Coast for forgery. That's 'Fancy Fingers' Finley."\par
Collig laughed. "Miss Hardy, you've got to do better than that."\par
"I'll find him yet," Aunt Gertrude said with determination.\par
"Maybe if you come along with us to find him-" Joe suggested half-jokingly.\par
"And don't think I wouldn't capture him if I did I" she retorted. "Just the same, good detectives can stay right at home and solve certain mysteries. They don't have to gallivant all over the countryside."\par
For the next hour \i she \i0 pored over the pictures. Every once in a while she would pause at one which resembled Breck. Finally she closed the last album with a sigh of disappointment.\par
"He's just not here," Aunt Gertrude said dejectedly. "But I know I've seen his picture somewhere," she vowed.\par
"Maybe he was in disguise, Aunt Gertrude," Joe suggested. He was disappointed, too, that she had not been able to put her finger on a photograph of the mysterious man, and neither he nor Frank could find him.\par
After telling Collig of the man's forgery, Frank asked for Breck's address.\par
"We'd better work quickly before he decides to leave town," Frank said.\par
The officer consulted his files for a moment. "Breck's registered at the Excelsior Hotel," he informed them, mentioning the name of a third-rate hotel in the waterfront section of Bayport.\par
After dropping off Aunt Gertrude, who wanted to do some shopping, the boys drove to the Excelsior.\par
"Have you a man named Wylie Breck staying here?" Frank asked the clerk.\par
The man consulted the register. "We did," he replied after a moment, "but he checked out."\par
The young detectives looked at each other in disappointment.\par
"I know," said Frank. "Let's phone his lawyer Miles Kamp. Maybe he can tell us where Breck is."\par
The boys hurried to a telephone booth. After a few moments, Kamp answered.\par
"Yes, this is Miles Kamp," came the familiar pompous voice. "May I be of service to you?"\par
Frank asked where he could find Breck.\par
"I'm dreadfully sorry, my boy, but I can't help you at all. I haven't the vaguest idea where he went."\par
As Frank hung up, he wondered if this were true. "No help from that source," he said to Joe in disgust.\par
As they passed the desk again, the clerk beckoned to them. They hurried over.\par
"Aren't you Frank and Joe Hardy?" the man asked.\par
The boys admitted that they were.\par
"I thought so," the clerk continued in a low tone. "I recognized you from your newspaper pictures. I didn't care much for that guy Breck. If you're tracking him down, I'll let you look through his room for any possible clues. Follow me."\par
"Thanks," Frank said.\par
A minute later the clerk let them into the vacant room, then started back downstairs.\par
The boys searched thoroughly, looking into drawers, the wastebasket, even under the mattress, but found nothing that might help them locate the mysterious leather-goods salesman.\par
"Looks as if we're stuck," Joe said dejectedly as they came out of the room.\par
"Maybe not. There's a chambermaid. Let's see if she knows anything about Breck," Frank suggested when he saw a woman coming down the corridor carrying a pile of linens.\par
The boys approached her and Frank explained that they were looking for some trace of Breck.\par
"Breck, Breck," repeated the woman slowly. "Seems like I recall the feller. Hard-looking type. Shooed me out of the room once. Acted very strange."\par
Suddenly her face lit up. "I do remember something!" she exclaimed. "A bit of brown wrapping paper."\par
Going to a closet, she began to dig through a pile of trash. Presently the chambermaid gave a triumphant cry.\par
"Here it is!" she called. "I emptied this out of Breck's room."\par
The boys scanned the paper hurriedly.\par
"I can make out a name! Philip York!" Frank exclaimed. "But the address is blurred!"\par
"Philip York," his brother repeated. "I wonder if he could be a friend of Breck."\par
Taking the paper to a window, Frank held it to let the light strike it obliquely. In this way, he had often deciphered smeared or smudged writing.\par
"I've got it," Frank went on, reading haltingly. "Twenty-four Dock Street, Southport," he concluded triumphantly.\par
The address was that of a town several miles from Bayport on Eagle Bay, where the boys had often gone cruising.\par
"Come on, Frank!" Joe urged excitedly. "Let's go and call on this Philip York!"\par
Within half an hour Frank was guiding their convertible through the crowded streets of the grimy waterfront section of Southport. Reaching Dock Street, Joe began to look at the house numbers.\par
"There it is!" he exclaimed. "Pull up, Frank."\par
Twenty-four Dock Street was a ramshackle tenement. As the boys walked through the open front door, a stocky man dressed in dirty work clothes brushed rudely by them into the hallway.\par
"Frank," Joe whispered, "he might be York."\par
With a bound, the boys followed the man up the rickety stairs.\par
"Say, mister," Joe called out, "we want to ask you some questions."\par
The man turned around and faced them. "Who do you think you're following?" he demanded angrily.\par
"We want some information," Frank said boldly.\par
"So you want info, do you?" the man replied. "Well, who are you and what's your business here? Get out of here before I throw you out." He raised his arm in a threatening motion.\par
Undaunted, the boys held their ground.\par
"You'll throw nobody out," Frank said in a quiet but determined voice. "Do you know a Wylie Breck?"\par
"No."\par
"Are you Philip York?"\par
The man surveyed the boys standing shoulder to shoulder. "No, I'm not," he answered. "What's the racket?"\par
Frank shrugged. "We heard they lived here. Thought we'd look 'em up."\par
"Oh, that's different. Well, I never heard of Wylie Breck, but there's a Philip York on the first floor," the stranger went on, somewhat calmed down.\par
The man pointed down the stairs. "He lives in that apartment. But I advise you kids to scram. You don't belong here. You'll get into trouble." He went up the stairs without explaining further.\par
Frank and Joe descended the stairs. The hallway was dark and had a musty odor. They rapped on the door of York's apartment.\par
After a few moments' wait they heard footsteps approaching the door.\par
"Get set, Frank, in case it's Breck and he slams the door in our faces," Joe whispered.\par
\i As \i0 the door was flung open the boys tensed themselves.\par
"What do you want?" An unshaven man, wearing a royal-blue sweater, challenged them. He was not Breck.\par
"We're looking for Wylie Breck and Philip York," Frank replied quickly, edging closer to the door.\par
"Breck? York?" the man rasped in a foggy voice. "Never heard of 'em. What business you got in this place, anyway?" he asked.\par
"We want to talk to them, that's all," Frank replied. "Maybe you've seen Breck around."\par
Frank described Breck, adding that he carried a suitcase full of leather goods.\par
"Never saw him," the man said.\par
Suddenly he raised his eyes and looked beyond the boys. Alert to danger, the boys turned.\par
As the door slammed behind them, they saw two dark shapes coming swiftly toward them.\par
"Look out!" Joe cried out.\par
\par
\par
CHAPTER IV\line\b\i The Telltale Moccasin\i0\par
\b0\par
THE Hardys were only half turned to meet the attack when the two men crashed into them, chest-high. Joe was knocked out, Frank stunned.\par
Frank instinctively lashed out at the men with both fists. One of the attackers sank to his knees, but the other thug, coming from behind, got a strangle hold on the boy which rendered him helpless.\par
The Hardys' assailants dragged them down the hallway, pushed them into a closet, and locked the door.\par
"Leave the key in," a voice ordered.\par
It was several seconds before Joe regained his senses and remembered what had happened.\par
"Who could those guys have been?" Frank rammed his body against the door to open it.\par
"Beats me. Let's try pounding first," Joe advised. "We don't want to pay for a broken door."\par
They thumped on the panel and waited. All was still. Then they began yelling:\par
"Help! Help!"\par
Presently they heard heavy footsteps coming down the hall. Was he friend or foe?\par
"I'm going to tackle him whoever he is," Joe said.\par
Before Frank could warn against it, the door opened and Joe charged the man outside. The two of them rolled on the floor in a heap.\par
"I've got him, Frank!" Joe yelled.\par
"Hey, lay off, fellows!" a familiar voice shouted.\par
"Chet Morton!" Frank exclaimed, recognizing their friend and helping him to his feet.\par
"Chet, how the dickens did you get here?" Joe demanded. "Gee, I'm sorry. I thought you might be one of the thugs who threw us in the closet."\par
"Hm!" said Chet as he dusted himself off. "I thought you would get in trouble, so I followed you from Bayport. My jalopy can't tear like yours. I nearly lost you, but a kid on the corner told me where you went."\par
"Good thing you came, Chet," Joe replied. "Sorry I was rough with you."\par
"That's okay," Chet said lightly. "Centers ought to be ready for surprise tackles."\par
"Let's talk again to that fellow in the blue sweater," Frank proposed. "Maybe he knows who hit us."\par
The trio hurried down the corridor, and Joe rapped on the door. No one answered. He pounded.\par
"Mighty mysterious," Frank commented. "That fellow knew we were in trouble. If he isn't in league with them, why didn't he help us out?"\par
"He must be a friend of Breck," Joe replied. "And that's why he didn't tell us that he was Philip York."\par
No one came to open the door. Either the man had gone out, or for reasons of his own would not answer.\par
"Let's report this whole business to the South-port police," said Frank. "There's nothing more we can do here."\par
"Now you're talking," agreed Chet. "This is a good place to stay away from."\par
After they had made a full statement at headquarters, and asked the sergeant to report any developments to Chief Collig, the boys drove back to Bayport.\par
Frank and Joe were puzzled by the day's events, but their determination to find Breck was stronger than ever.\par
Arriving home, they were greeted by their mother.\par
"Come on, boys," she said. "Hurry and wash. We'll eat in a few minutes."\par
After dinner, which included a second helping of chocolate walnut cake, Frank said:\par
"Joe, I have an idea. Why don't we try tracking down the manufacturer of that key case Mother bought from Breck? In that way, perhaps we'll be able to find out who he really is."\par
"Good idea. Let's start now."\par
They went into their father's study, where Mrs. Hardy had put the new key case. Joe turned it over carefully in his hand. There was no name on it.\par
"But here's something inside," he announced.\par
Imprinted on the leather, in a corner of the case, was an odd mark:\par
\tab\tab\par
The boys gave a sigh of satisfaction.\par
"Now we've got something definite to go on," Frank said, smiling. "Tomorrow we'll show it to a leather-goods dealer and ask him what manufacturer uses this mark."\par
After football practice the next afternoon, they hurried straight to the shop of their white-haired friend Mr. Nobbly.\par
"We'd like to find out who made this," Frank explained, showing the key case. "Here's the imprint. Can you tell us who uses this trademark?"\par
Mr. Nobbly examined the mark closely. He shook his head slowly. "Sorry, boys, I never saw nor heard of that mark in all my thirty-five years in this business."\par
"Then it's probably some private maker's?" Frank asked.\par
"No doubt. It's fine, hand-tooled work. But it would be like hunting for a penny in the mud of Barmet Bay to find him."\par
Frank looked at Joe in disappointment. Another clue gone up in smoke!\par
"Come on," Joe said. "We'll keep checking."\par
They thanked Mr. Nobbly and left the store. For the next few days the Hardys called at every possible place in their quest for the maker of the key case.\par
They went to all the leather-goods shops in Bayport and examined key cases, wallets, handbags, and luggage. They even checked with shoe stores. But no one had ever seen such a mark.\par
Finally the boys had to postpone their search and settle down to hard football practice. Saturday came with the big game against Hopkinsville.\par
Frank was gloomy as the team donned their uniforms in the locker room.\par
"I guess it's no use trying to trace that symbol," he said dejectedly to Joe, pulling on his jersey.\par
"Looks as if you're right," his brother replied. "Well, let's forget about it for a while. We have a game to play, and you know what a whale of a team Hopkinsville has this year."\par
As they trotted along the corridor of the field house, Frank spied a moccasin lying on the cement floor. Ordinarily he would not have done any more than kick it out of the way. But being interested now in everything made of leather he bent down and picked it up.\par
"Joe, look!" he exulted. "The telltale mark!"\par
"Sure enough," Joe cried. "I wonder who dropped this." He queried the members of his team as they came from the field house. None owned the moccasin.\par
"Must be someone from Hopkinsville," Frank mused. "We'll find out later."\par
He took it along to the bench. The warm-up period was over and they were waiting for the whistle when one of the Hopkinsville players ran by. He noticed Frank holding the moccasin.\par
"Say, what are you fellows doing with that?" he asked. "It belongs to one of our ends-George Parks."\par
"Where is he?" inquired Joe. "We want to ask him about this moccasin."\par
The Hopkinsville player pointed. "He's the tall guy there."\par
At that moment the referee blew his whistle, signaling that the game was to begin.\par
The biggest crowd in years had gathered to watch the contest. Hopkinsville won the toss and elected to defend the north goal with the wind at their backs. Frank and Joe waited tensely in their positions as the Hopkinsville hooter carefully placed the ball for the kickoff.\par
"Here it comes!" Frank cried. "Joe, it's headed right for you!"\par
Joe caught the end-over-end kickoff on the ten-yard line. Twisting and dodging, he carried the ball to mid-field. The Bayport stands cheered loudly.\par
Frank gained a couple of yards on the next play on a smash-through tackle. Then, on the following play, Joe faded back and tossed a short pass to the left end, Tony Prito. The dark-haired, wiry youth, a close friend of the Hardys, took the ball for a first down on the Hopkinsville thirty-five.\par
A couple of line bucks by Biff Hooper, another of their special friends, gained a few yards, and finally on the fourth down Joe faded back for a long pass.\par
Frank shot down the field like a streak of lightning, the ball sailing straight toward him. But just as he was reaching for it, a Hopkinsville player batted it down, and the opponents took over.\par
Frank moved along behind his linemen, grunting words of confidence to each in turn.\par
But in three plays Hopkinsville was on the Bayport four!\par
"This is the big one," Frank thought. "We've got to hold. This is the time to call the secret defensive play we've been practicing all week."\par
As the teams lined up for fourth down, Frank called out crisply:\par
"86X!"\par
Both Bayport tackles, instead of making the usual defensive charge, remained fixed in their positions and let the offensive linemen come to them. Through the tiny space created by this forward motion, Chet and Frank knifed into the enemy backfield and made havoc of the play, Chet making the tackle and stopping Newman, the Hopkinsville ace, in his tracks. The secret play had worked! The threat was halted! The remainder of the period was chiefly a punting duel between Frank and Newman. Each would run two ground plays and then punt. After several such exchanges, it became clear that Frank was getting more yardage with his high booming kicks that spiraled deep into enemy territory every time.\par
The Hopkinsville coach changed his strategy. He called a fresh end off the bench, briefed him with an arm around his thick shoulders, and sent him into the game. The team seemed to get a new life as he came trotting on. This meant their favorite pass play!\par
Joe, just before he dropped back to his safety zone, got a quick glimpse of the replacement. He recognized him as George Parks!\par
"Now I'll be able to find out about the moccasin," Joe thought, but his excitement was lost in the barking of signals by the Hopkinsville quarterback.\par
Parks drifted down-field, got by Chet, and was lengthening his stride to take a long pass over his right shoulder, when Joe came racing across and knocked the ball right off his fingertips.\par
Joe ran back a few steps to pick up the ball. Tossing it to the referee, he turned quickly to talk to George Parks about the moccasin. But Parks had left the game and was almost off the field! He had been sent in for one play and that was all.\par
The first half ended in a scoreless tie. Each team went directly to its locker room.\par
As the Hardys came running side by side onto the field for the second half, Frank whispered to Joe, "We'll speak to Parks right after the game. That moccasin is a vital clue."\par
After the half-time interval Joe fastened his headgear a little more securely, took a reassuring look at George Parks on the Hopkinsville bench, and signaled for the kickoff.\par
The second half was a seesaw affair, with each team getting breaks and losing them.\par
With seconds to go in the last quarter, the Hopkinsville team suddenly fanned out in a widespread formation. Bayport shifted with them. Newman called his signals. Suddenly Joe noticed that Chet had not shifted. He was standing with a dazed look on his face. Then it dawned on Joe!\par
Each pass had been made into Chet's zone. He must have been hurt on that line smash. No doubt Newman would be throwing in there again!\par
The ball was snapped to Newman. He began to fade way back. He threw a long, lazy pass that soared over Chet's head toward the Bayport goal line.\par
The timekeeper's gun sounded as the ball was in flight. As soon as the ball was dead, the game would be officially over!\par
Joe, who had anticipated the play, was at the goal line, a step ahead of the Bayport pass receiver. He leaped up, wrenched the ball out of the grasp of his opponent, whirled, and scooted across the field, just outside of his own goal line.\par
At the fifty-yard line Frank threw a vicious block at the fastest enemy tackier, and Joe sprinted into the clear, with the wild uproar of the Bayport stands in his ears, straight down the sideline to the Hopkinsville goal.\par
The score was Bayport 6, Hopkinsville 0! Pandemonium reigned!\par
As Frank sent the ball straight through the crossbars, the gun sounded the end of the game.\par
Bayport had won 7-0 on Joe Hardy's one-hundred-yard dash for a touchdown! Frank hugged his brother, delirious with joy.\par
"What a run! There's never been a touchdown run \i that \i0 long in the history of Bayport High!"\par
"Yea, Hardy boys!" the Bayport fans shouted as they poured onto the field.\par
With cheers and singing, Frank and Joe were borne off the field on the shoulders of their teammates. When at last they were set down, more fans crowded around to pommel the boys and shake their hands.\par
"Joe! Joe!" Frank shouted over the tumult. "We must see George Parks before he gets away!"\par
But the boys were trapped by their admirers as the Hopkinsville team dejectedly disappeared from the field. Fifteen minutes went by. But finally the Hardys broke loose.\par
They raced toward the parking lot, but when they reached it, they saw the Hopkinsville bus pulling out!\par
\par
\par
CHAPTER V\line\b\i Buried Treasure\par
\i0\par
\b0 FRANK and Joe gave chase, but it was too late. In a cloud of dust, the bus disappeared down the road, leaving the young detectives panting in the roadway.\par
As they trudged back toward the field house, Joe said, "I wonder what Parks did about his moccasin. It was still under our bench a few minutes ago."\par
The boys retrieved it.\par
"What say we return this to him tomorrow?" Frank asked.\par
"You bet."\par
They would have driven over that evening, but there was a school dance. Chet's attractive dark-haired sister Iola was going with Joe, and pretty blond Callie Shaw with Frank.\par
Sunday afternoon the boys looked up Parks' address in the telephone directory, then drove to Hopkinsville.\par
"There's the house, Frank," Joe called out as they came to a tree-shaded ranch-style dwelling.\par
The tall, good-looking ballplayer answered the door.\par
"Hello, George," Joe greeted him.\par
"Joe and Frank Hardy!" the boy replied. "Come on in. Say, I'll never forget you fellows after yesterday's game."\par
"It sure was close," Frank said.\par
"What brings you to Hopkinsville?"\par
"We're returning some of your property." Frank held out a bag containing the moccasin.\par
"Thanks," Parks said, after Frank had explained about finding the shoe. "I hated to lose that. Those loafers are the most comfortable shoes I own. I had to wear my football shoes home."\par
Taking off their overcoats, Frank and Joe quickly outlined their special reason for coming and pointed to the R mark inside the moccasin.\par
"What we want to know," said Frank, "is where you bought them."\par
"Golly," George replied quickly, "I know where \i I \i0 got them, but, I can't tell you where they were purchased."\par
"You didn't buy them yourself?" Joe asked.\par
"No. My uncle gave them to me as a present for my birthday last spring. All I know is that the moccasins were made by an Indian tribe. But what tribe I couldn't tell you," he concluded.\par
"Could you find out, George? It's important. It may help to catch a thief!"\par
"Good night!" Parks exclaimed. "That's right. You fellows are detectives, aren't you? Well, my uncle lives a couple of blocks from here. I'll ask him."\par
He went to the phone, but the line was busy, so he suggested that they walk over. His uncle Ben was intrigued by the Hardys' story of their quest for the maker of the leather goods.\par
"I remember those moccasins well," he said, drawing on his pipe. "I bought them from a stranger on a train. I never saw him before, and I've never seen him since."\par
"An Indian?" Frank asked.\par
"No."\par
"Did he mention the name of the tribe?"\par
Uncle Ben shook his head. "No, he didn't- just said he'd bought them from an Indian and that they were too small for him."\par
The Hardys thanked Mr. Parks and George and started back to Bayport.\par
"It looks as though we're up a blind alley again. All of our clues lead us nowhere," Frank muttered.\par
"You know," his brother said thoughtfully, "if that mark means anything, the name of the tribe may begin with an R. Maybe we ought to do some research on Indians."\par
"Good idea," Frank agreed. "I wonder," he added thoughtfully, "if Breck can be an Indian."\par
"He didn't look like a full-blooded one."\par
"No, I meant a half-breed."\par
"I'll settle for a quarter."\par
Presently a familiar house came into view.\par
"Let's stop at the Mortons'," Joe suggested. "I'm getting hungry, anyway."\par
Chet and Iola were home. Iola was mixing a batch of waffles under her brother's direction.\par
"We're just in time." Joe grinned. "Hope you've got plenty."\par
"Sure," Chet answered. "Iola, make twice as much batter. That'll be enough for a starter."\par
"I don't know about that," his sister replied teasingly. "Perhaps I'd better mix three times as much."\par
The chunky football center was known for his appetite, and despite needling from his friends, never reduced his intake of food.\par
Supper was a jolly affair, but eventually the talk got around to the mystery of Wylie Breck. Frank told of the slim clue they had picked up from Mr. Parks.\par
He concluded the story by telling them that the moccasin had been made by an Indian tribe. As he was saying, "If only we knew the name of a tribe that begins with R," Iola and Chet looked at each other strangely.\par
"You know of one?" Joe asked.\par
"N-no," Chet replied, and in a moment disappeared from the room.\par
The Hardys continued to eat waffles with syrup.\par
As Joe got up to get more butter from the refrigerator, he gave a strangled cry. Frank turned to see what had startled him.\par
Standing in the doorway was an Indian in battle regalia!\par
He raised his hand commandingly. Then a deep but strangely familiar voice intoned: "I am Chief Wallapatookunk."\par
"Chet!" whooped the Hardys, roaring with laughter as they recognized their buddy.\par
"Where in the world did you get that outfit?" Frank asked.\par
Chet himself was struggling to maintain a dignified and fierce look.\par
"This Indian warrior's suit," he replied solemnly. "Chief say you his prisoners." He pointed to Iola. "Bring um white girl to Wallapatookunk."\par
Iola now was giggling but pretended to be alarmed and shrank toward Joe.\par
"I will defend this maiden to the last arrow!" Joe said, then added, "Have a heart, Chet, before I die laughing. Where did you get that Indian costume?"\par
"It's this way, fellows," Chet began, pulling out a handkerchief and wiping some of the red, black, and white crayon from his face. "My greatgrandfather was a member of the Pashunk tribe."\par
"What!" Frank cried.\par
"Honest Injun," Chet insisted, "my greatgrandfather belonged to the Pashunk tribe."\par
"He's right," Iola chimed in.\par
"Great-grandfather Ezekiel Morton was honorary Chief Wallapatookunk of the Pashunks. This getup I'm wearing is a ceremonial outfit used only on special occasions. It's been in our family for generations, and I just thought of it again when you mentioned those Indian moccasins."\par
"What does Wallapatookunk mean?" Frank asked.\par
"Gee, fellows," Chet stammered, "you really don't want to know, do you?"\par
"We certainly do," Frank insisted.\par
"Well, it means 'Eat-a-Whole-Moose,'" Chet answered reluctantly.\par
"Boy, your great-grandfather must have had some appetite. Say, why didn't your folks call you Ezekiel?"\par
"Whoever heard of a center called Ezekiel?" Chet countered, ignoring the gibe.\par
"We don't know exactly how our great-grandfather got the Indian name," Iola spoke up, "but we do know a very strange legend that he used to tell. It has been handed down in our family."\par
"What is it?" Joe asked eagerly.\par
"According to the legend, a fabulous treasure is buried in the territory where the Pashunks used to live!"\par
"Buried treasure!" The Hardys whistled in amazement.\par
"Where?" Joe inquired.\par
"No one knows."\par
"But there must be some clue," Frank insisted.\par
"Yes," Chet assented. "The legend says the treasure is buried in a crisscross shadow!"\par
"The shadow of what?" Joe asked.\par
"That's what we don't know, but I sure wish we could find the treasure," Chet concluded.\par
Just then the doorbell rang and Iola excused herself to answer it.\par
"Hi, Frank! Hello, Joe! Chet! What in the world!" cried Callie Shaw as she saw the boy's costume and his multicolored streaked face.\par
"Callie," Joe said solemnly, with a sweep of his arm, "let me present Great Chief Walla-er -anyhow, heap big wheel among Indians I"\par
Callie, though still puzzled, joined the outburst of laughter at Joe's introduction of the disguised Chet.\par
Then Frank brought her up to date on news in the Morton household and also what he and Joe had learned at Hopkinsville.\par
"You've really made progress in your detecting," Callie commented. "If you could only find out something further about that R imprint."\par
"Say, why don't we get out our collection of old Indian books, Chet?" Iola spoke up. "Maybe we'll find some tribes that begin with R."\par
"And then we'll check on whether they're the ones who do leatherwork," Frank added enthusiastically.\par
Iola excused herself and returned a few minutes later with an armload of old volumes.\par
Immediately all the young people started thumbing through the books, intently scanning the fine print. The pages were yellowed with age.\par
There were dozens of tribes that no longer existed-names that had meant so much in the early days of the country-Abnakis, Shawnees, Narragansetts, and others that reminded the Bay-port High students of the exciting days of the early colonists.\par
"This tribe we're looking for is probably so small that it didn't even make history," remarked Joe, breaking the silence. Everyone nodded agreement, but kept on leafing the pages determinedly.\par
\i But there was not a single tribe that began with an r!\i0\par
Finally it was time for the Hardys to start home, since they did not wish to break football training rules. Frank rode with Callie as far as her house, with Joe following, then transferred to the convertible.\par
"I guess we're at the end of the Indian trail with that moccasin," Joe remarked.\par
"We may still find the R tribe," Frank said more hopefully. "I'm not giving up yet."\par
"I'm with you on that score," Joe agreed as they turned the corner near the Hardy home.\par
Suddenly Frank gave a start and sat bolt upright. "Look!" he whispered excitedly. "Coming out of that window!"\par
Joe followed his brother's gaze to the second floor of the Hardy house. In the moonlight they could see a man climbing out!\par
Frank cut the engine and stopped at the curb. The boys leaped from the car and dashed up the driveway.\par
As they looked up again, the intruder was dropping to the roof of the kitchen porch. Then a cloud passed in front of the moon and hid the scene in darkness.\par
"Come on! He mustn't get away!" Joe cried.\par
The boys heard a thud on the ground, and reached the porch just as the moon broke through the clouds.\par
\i They could see no one!\i0\par
In the second that the clouds had obscured the moon, the intruder had disappeared as if the earth had swallowed him up!\par
\par
\par
CHAPTER VI\line\b\i An Elusive Suspect\par
\i0\par
\b0 WHERE had the man who had climbed out the second-story window gone?\par
"Quick!" Joe said to his brother. "I'll circle this side of the house. You take the other."\par
Finding no one, they searched the neighboring yards. It was no use. The intruder had disappeared.\par
"Let's go inside and see if he took anything," Frank urged.\par
Noticing that several lights had been turned on upstairs, the boys dashed to the second floor.\par
"It's Frank and Joe," Frank called. "Are you all right, Mother?"\par
"Oh, boys, what a relief to see you!" Mrs. Hardy cried as they reached the hall.\par
Aunt Gertrude stood menacingly, an umbrella clutched in her hand.\par
"We saw a man crawling out of the second-story window," Frank told them.\par
"Then why didn't you catch him?" Aunt Gertrude bristled.\par
"We tried," Frank confessed, "but he got away."\par
"Did he steal anything?" Joe put in. "Did you see him?"\par
"See him?" Aunt Gertrude echoed with indignation. "We saw him, and if I ever get that fellow, I'll give him the thrashing of his life."\par
"Aunt Gertrude and I came home from the movies. When we got upstairs we heard a noise in your father's study," Mrs. Hardy explained. "We looked in and saw a masked man. As soon as he spotted us, he dived for the window and climbed out."\par
"What was he doing?" Frank asked.\par
"He was standing in front of the file cabinet with a key in his hand!"\par
The boys rushed into Mr. Hardy's study and examined the file carefully. Apparently it had not been disturbed.\par
"Good thing we changed that lock," Joe said.\par
"Right. But the criminal might have forced it open." Frank turned to his mother and aunt. "I guess you frightened him off in time."\par
"I wonder what he was after," Joe pondered.\par
"It could be almost anything," Frank replied thoughtfully. "Let's fine-tooth-comb this room. Maybe the fellow left a clue that may help us track him down."\par
They examined the study from wall to wall but found nothing. As Joe leaned against the cabinet, a disappointed frown on his face, suddenly something caught his eye. Reaching down, he pulled at a bit of wool snagged on the corner of one drawer.\par
"We missed this," he said. "Oh boy! What a clue!"\par
Triumphantly he flashed a strand of royal-blue wool! "That man in the house in Southport! Remember? He was wearing a royal-blue sweater!"\par
"Correct." Frank beamed. "Now we're beginning to get somewhere on this case!"\par
"That proves Breck \i did \i0 take the key!" cried Joe. "After he skipped Bayport, either he or his lawyer gave it to the man in the royal-blue sweater and he came here tonight."\par
"Maybe those two guys who slugged us in that Southport tenement house were Breck and Kamp!" Frank reasoned. "They were just arriving to give Mr. Blue Sweater the key."\par
"Everything ties together." Joe nodded in satisfaction. "But the important question's still not answered. What did this gang want from Dad's file?"\par
"Let's go back to Southport tomorrow and call on that blue-sweater guy again," Frank proposed.\par
Since the football squad was excused from practice on Monday, the Hardys were able to start for Southport as soon as classes were over.\par
"How about coming along, Chet?" Frank asked as they got ready to leave.\par
"Sorry, fellows. I promised Dad I'd help around home. But listen, you two, don't get yourselves in the hospital. We've got a tough game to play on Saturday and-"\par
"Where're you going?" Tony Prito spoke up. "Maybe I can be your bodyguard."\par
"Swell."\par
The three boys drove to the dock where the Hardys' small powerboat the \i Sleuth \i0 was moored. They would make the trip to Southport by water.\par
When they arrived, Frank and Joe asked Tony to guard the \i Sleuth \i0 while they were gone. Then they headed up a steep cobblestoned alley to the street and walked into the main entrance of the tenement where Philip York lived.\par
Joe rapped on the apartment door while Frank kept an eye on the dim corridor to avoid another surprise attack.\par
The door was opened by the man they had come to see. He was wearing the telltale blue sweater.\par
"What do you want?" he asked roughly.\par
"To talk to you."\par
The man's eyes widened when he recognized his callers. "You boys are going to get hurt coming around here," he said threateningly. "I can't give you any information."\par
"Oh no?" Joe retorted skeptically, then shot the question, "What were you doing in our house last night?"\par
"Your house? I've never been near the place in my life," York replied angrily.\par
"That's your story," Frank spoke up. "Here, take a look at this," he said, forcing his way in and suddenly confronting the man with the piece of blue yarn. "It came from that sweater you're wearing," he declared, pointing to a tear in the front of it.\par
The man looked blank, then recovered. "Maybe it did, maybe it didn't. Anyway, it ain't my sweater," he said defensively. "I borrowed it."\par
"We don't believe you," Frank answered firmly. Both boys were in the room now. "You'd better start talking."\par
"Look, fellows," York said meekly. "Take it easy on a guy that ain't to blame, will you? I'll do anything you ask. You've got the goods on me."\par
The Hardys had not expected to get a confession that easily. They looked at each other with satisfaction. At last they were making headway on the case!\par
"Come along to the police station with us," Frank said sternly. "They'll want to hear what you have to say."\par
"Okay," the man replied nervously. "I'll have to get my coat out of the bedroom. Wait here."\par
Before they could object, he turned, went into an adjoining room, and closed the door.\par
