"You come to unfriendly tribe. Very dangerous people."\par
"Dangerous?" Frank said skeptically. "What's so dangerous about an Indian tribe these days?"\par
"You listen to warning, paleface," the man continued, anger in his tones. "Tribe guard deep secret. No want visitors."\par
With that he turned on his heel and disappeared among the trees. The boys looked at each other dumbfounded.\par
Chet paled. "S-a-a-a-y, fellows," he said shakily, "maybe we'd better take his advice and turn back."\par
"Not on your life," Joe replied determinedly.\par
Frank agreed, adding, "I'll bet that fellow isn't even a member of the tribe. That accent he had was too thick. No real Indian talks like that these days. I'm sure he's a phony."\par
"You mean he faked everything-the Indian rig and the accent?" Chet demanded.\par
"Sure."\par
"Then who is he?"\par
"One of the gang we're trying to track down."\par
"You're right, Frank!" Joe exclaimed. "Quick! Before he gets away, let's follow him!"\par
\par
\par
CHAPTER X\line\b\i Tom-toms\par
\i0\par
\b0 THE boys crashed through the thick brush in pursuit of the strange Indian.\par
"Where'd he go?" Chet puffed.\par
"Here are fresh footprints!" Frank exclaimed. "Come on!"\par
They raced along, following the tracks Frank had observed. The narrow, rocky path wound deeper into the dim, silent forest.\par
The trail suddenly twisted sharply to the right. Frank, still in the lead, held up his hand, signaling a halt.\par
The trio stood still, looking intently for any indication of which way the man had gone. They came to the conclusion that he had jumped from stone to stone, losing his pursuers completely.\par
"We may as well continue on to the Ramapan village after we have a snack," Frank decided.\par
The boys quickly ate sandwiches they had brought along and drank from a sparkling mountain spring.\par
As they set off again, Chet cried out tensely: "Listen!"\par
The Hardys paused. The sound that came to\b  \b0 them was a muffled, regular beat.\par
"Tom-toms!" Frank exclaimed.\par
Chet turned pale and looked nervously about him. "S-a-a-a-y, fe-l-l-ows, those tom-toms-maybe that man we just met was right. What if those Indians are getting ready to attack us!"\par
Frank and Joe broke into laughter.\par
"Aren't you young Chief Wallapatookunk?"\par
Chet blushed furiously. "Come on," he said with a sudden show of bravery. "Let's go."\par
They moved along another quarter of a mile without further disturbance. Then a fawn loped swiftly across their path as if in frightened flight. As it disappeared, the reason became evident. An Indian boy about their own age came out of the woods. He stopped short upon seeing them.\par
He was dressed in clothes similar to theirs, but had coppery skin and straight black hair.\par
"Hello," he said pleasantly. "What are you fellows doing so deep in the woods? Lost?"\par
Neither Chet nor the Hardys answered at once. They were staring at the moccasins the boy was wearing. On each toe section was the mysterious R, outlined with multicolored beads.\par
"No, we're not lost," Frank replied finally. "We're heading for the Ramapan village."\par
The Indian noticed the boys' eyes riveted on his moccasins. "What is it?" he asked with a puzzled air.\par
"Where did you get those moccasins?" Joe questioned him excitedly.\par
"Why, right here," replied the youth. "We Ramapans make them."\par
"You are a Ramapan?" Frank asked.\par
"Sure."\par
Joe seized the Indian's hand joyfully. "Are we glad to see you! We've been trying for days to find out who makes those moccasins!"\par
"Well, follow me, then," the boy said, smiling. "I can show you plenty more like these. By the way, I'm Ted Whitestone. My father is Chief Oscar Whitestone of the Ramapans."\par
The Hardys and Chet introduced themselves. Then Ted turned in the direction of his village.\par
"Quite a difference between Ted and that man we met on the trail," Joe whispered to his brother as Chet asked Ted questions about his tribe.\par
"No, we don't live in teepees," the Indian boy replied with a smile. "Just regular houses like everybody else. And we don't dress up in feathers and big war bonnets, either. I hope I'm not disillusioning you fellows," he added with a grin.\par
"But we heard tom-toms," said Chet.\par
"One of the men was practicing for our ceremonial dance that we always perform this time of year," Ted explained.\par
"And we saw an Indian dressed in fringed leather just a few minutes before we met you," Chet told him. "He had a peculiar accent."\par
Ted's eyes widened in surprise. "That's funny. I can't imagine who it might be. Nobody in our tribe dresses like that or talks with an accent, except old Long Heart, and he's all right. What did the man want?"\par
Frank told him of the stranger's warning about the Ramapans and how they would resent the boys' presence because the tribe was guarding a secret.\par
"That's crazy," Ted declared. "I can't understand why a stranger would want to keep you from coming here. I'll speak to my father about this."\par
The young detectives glanced at one another. Were they bringing trouble to the Ramapans, or were they running into some?\par
"Here we are," Ted announced as the path suddenly widened and opened into a spacious cleared area.\par
The Ramapan village consisted of a main street with stores and several side roads with small, neat houses, most of them painted white. Off to one side stood a long, low building with many windows in it, and in the other direction was a large field which Ted said was used for athletics and tribal conferences.\par
"This is my home," Ted said, stopping before a small white house with green shutters.\par
A tall, distinguished-looking man, whom the youth resembled, met them at the door.\par
"Dad," Ted addressed him, "I'd like you to meet Frank and Joe Hardy and Chet Morton."\par
The boys and Chief Oscar Whitestone shook hands, then smiling warmly, the man added, "Come in, boys. You've had a long hike. We don't often see strangers this deep in the forest."\par
When Frank told briefly why they had come, Chief Whitestone was greatly interested.\par
"We'll show you the factory where we make our leather products," he said.\par
The boys followed Chief Whitestone and his son outside. As the group walked toward the factory, the villagers gave cheery greetings to the head of their tribe. Reaching the long, low building which the boys had noticed before, the chief led the way inside.\par
"Here's where we do our handicraft work," Ted spoke up proudly, his arm encompassing the long room with a single broad sweep.\par
As they walked down one of the aisles, Ted's father explained the various kinds of work the craftsmen were doing. "This man is making moccasins," he said.\par
The visitors peered over the shoulder of an old Indian who was carefully molding strips of leather over a wooden block. They could see the outlines of the footwear taking shape.\par
"Those workers over there are sewing key cases," Chief Whitestone pointed out. The boys watched as one of them punched a hole in the leather with an awl and expertly drew the thread through.\par
Frank produced the key case their mother had bought from Breck. "Ever see this before?" he asked Chief Whitestone.\par
The Indian examined the leather article carefully. "Certainly. It was made right here," he answered. He was about to hand it back when he took another look inside. "Just as I thought, Ted. This is made of that special leather we had. It was in that suitcase full of our work that was stolen a few weeks ago." Turning to Frank, he added, "Where did you come across this?"\par
The boy explained that they were amateur detectives and related the events of the past few days concerning Breck, who had sold the key case to Mrs. Hardy, Kamp his lawyer, and the man in the blue sweater who had tried to gain access to Mr. Hardy's secret file cabinet.\par
"I suppose you have no idea who took the suitcase, Chief Whitestone," Joe said, unable to hide his disappointment.\par
"I'm afraid I haven't," the chief replied. "You see," he explained, "all our work is carried out of here in suitcases, since we can't get a truck or car through the trail. Then it's taken by train to Williamsville, where it's turned over to a distributor. He markets everything for us."\par
The boys listened carefully as the chief went on, "A couple of weeks ago our messenger left a suitcase unguarded in the railroad station, and when he came back to get the bag, it was gone. That's all we know about it."\par
"I'd say we ought to leave here at once and track down Breck," said Frank, "if it weren't for that strange man we met in the woods. He's probably connected with this mystery. I think we'll stay around Lantern Junction for a few days and try to find him."\par
"I wish you luck," Chief Whitestone said. When they were outside again, he turned to face Frank and Joe.\par
"So you're detectives," he remarked. "And you're staying around here for a while."\par
"That's right," Frank replied, wondering what the chief was leading up to.\par
Smiling at them, he asked, "How would you like to solve a mystery for me-an old mystery of the Ramapans?"\par
\par
\par
CHAPTER XI\line\b\i A Jeweled Dagger\par
\i0\par
\b0 ANOTHER mystery to solve!\par
"We'll do our best, Chief Whitestone," Frank said.\par
"And when he tells you that," Chet spoke up, "it means they'll solve it."\par
Ted and his father smiled as the young detectives blushed at the compliment.\par
"When can we start?" Joe asked. "We'd like to begin right now because we're due back at school in a week or so."\par
"Yes, and it depends a little on where we'll have to go," Frank added. "Is it far away?"\par
"You can begin right here and now," the chief replied. "In fact, you'll have to solve the mystery in the next few days or else wait a whole year."\par
With this baffling introduction he invited the boys to go back to his home and hear the full story. Seated before an open fire in a cozy room filled with Indian relics, he began the strange tale.\par
"We Ramapans are an old tribe. We were once a great and powerful nation, a leader among the Indians in this part of the country.\par
"But as the years passed, and the white men spread out, our territories grew smaller. Our people became fewer in number as tribal warfare and sickness took their toll. Gradually the Ramapans' power was so weakened that we were forced to move north. This was many generations ago.\par
"Then, finally the wars stopped, and modern medicine cut down our death rate. We became prosperous, but still we were small and missed our former greatness," he said with a faraway look.\par
"The tribe carefully held on to its savings from fishing and trapping. Then fifty-nine years ago the leaders made a decision. With my father as chief, they decided to pool their resources and move down from the wild north country. The place they chose was this very acreage, the site where our ancestors had lived."\par
The boys had scarcely moved as the fascinating tale unfolded.\par
"My father and the tribe bought this land from the estate of a man named York."\par
York! The name of one of the suspected gang!\par
"Was his name Philip York?" Frank asked.\par
"No," Chief Whitestone replied. "It was Amos York. But after the tribe set up their new home, they didn't find the peace and security they had expected."\par
"What happened?" Joe asked.\par
The chief had paused to strike a match to his long pipe. He puffed a few times, then continued. "A neighboring tribe started to raid the Ramapans. They came every night, stealing and destroying our property and striking terror in the hearts of our people. But the Ramapans fought back even against heavy odds.\par
"My father was fearful the enemy would steal our deed to the property, as well as other valuable tribal records. So he buried them secretly, together with a jeweled dagger worth thousands of dollars that the Ramapans had had in their possession for generations. They had confiscated it after a battle with a French army two hundred years previously."\par
"Where did your father bury the papers and the dagger?" Frank asked him.\par
Chief Whitestone shook his head. "That's the mystery. Shortly afterward, he became ill and finally we realized he was dying.\par
"According to the laws of our tribe, I would become chief. Everyone knew my father had buried the papers and the dagger, but the place was a secret. So I asked him where they were.\par
"He was sinking rapidly, but he opened his eyes with great will power and whispered: 'My son - my son - papers - dagger - buried where a crisscross shadow is cast in the light of the hunter's moon."\par
As the chief stopped speaking, there was complete silence for several seconds, then the Hardys looked at Chet. His face wore a smug look, as if to say: "There \i is \i0 a treasure buried in a crisscross shadow!"\par
Chief Whitestone continued after a moment. "That was the only clue my father gave and I've never been able to find the place."\par
"It doesn't sound like an easy task," Frank remarked, "We-"\par
"That's not all," Chief Whitestone interrupted. "Not long ago two strangers appeared in the village. They said they wished to buy our land and were prepared to offer a fair price.\par
" 'No,' I told them, 'we wouldn't sell for all the money in the world. This is our home. The tribe has grown and prospered here after many generations of hardship. Our land is not for sale.' "\par
"But that didn't end it," Ted took up the story. "The men were insistent. Finally, one of them got mad and started to yell. 'Look, Chief,' he said to my father, Tm warning you! You'd better sell to us if you know what's good for you.' "\par
"That's right." Chief Whitestone nodded. " 'What do you mean?' I asked them.\par
" 'Just this,' the man replied. 'This land isn't yours.'\par
"I laughed at that, but he said, 'You think it's funny, eh? Well, we can prove you haven't got a clear title!' Then they stomped out of the house and disappeared.\par
"I'm afraid those men will find the deed before we do and steal it," Chief Whitestone said. "Unfortunately we have no other proof of ownership. The courthouse where our deed was recorded burned a few years ago and the papers were lost."\par
"Then those men can make it very hard for you," Joe said.\par
"Yes. After the fire, ads were run in the papers for people to bring in their deeds and have them recorded again, but we couldn't do that, of course."\par
"So it was easy for those men to find out your deed is missing," Frank surmised. "Well, we'll certainly try to find it for you."\par
"Haven't you any protection?" Chet interposed.\par
"Yes," the chief said. "After sixty years of possession, the tribe will own the land automatically -even without a deed. It's a state law. But we have several months to go before the time is up. Until then, we're at the mercy of anyone who finds those papers! And we can't be certain someone hasn't already taken them, of course."\par
"I doubt it," Frank commented. "If they had, either the papers would have been returned by honest people, or you would have had trouble before this with real thieves."\par
"How about those men who were here?" Chief Whitestone asked.\par
"I don't think that they would have offered to buy the land if they could have gotten it free."\par
"But I'll bet they're looking for the deed," Joe remarked. "So it's going to be a race. Let's get started!"\par
"I like your enthusiasm." The chief smiled. "But first I suggest we have something to eat. And later, why don't you move in here so you can be handy to your work?"\par
"Thank you," Frank replied. "We'll do that. Along with solving your mystery, we'll do some sleuthing on our own case."\par
By the time they had finished a meal of roast deer, corn bread, and fried apples prepared by Mrs. Whitestone, it had grown dark.\par
"You'd better make do tonight," Ted suggested. "You can go back and get your things at the hotel tomorrow."\par
The boys accepted Ted's hospitality and slept on cots in his room.\par
After breakfast the next morning, Joe said, "First thing we'll have to do is move our belongings in from town."\par
"Right you are," Frank agreed. "But there's no need for all of us to go back. I'll go and put all we need in one bag and check the others."\par
"Then Chet and I will start hunting around here for clues," Joe declared.\par
Chet went to question some of the older men of the tribe. Joe ambled along the street until he reached the leathercraft building. Nonchalantly he walked around it, to observe the layout of the structure.\par
"Guess I'll go inside," Joe told himself. "Maybe if I talk with some of the workers-"\par
The sound of a door opening interrupted his thoughts. He stood motionless as he saw one of the craftsmen emerge from the rear entrance. Joe ducked behind a tree and watched as the man looked intently in every direction.\par
"He acts as though he doesn't want to be seen," Joe thought.\par
Abruptly the man turned and set out briskly through the forest. Joe trailed him noiselessly.\par
Suddenly the Indian stopped and Joe concealed himself behind an evergreen. The man began stripping bark from a tree, all the while whistling in a carefree manner.\par
Joe, puzzled, arose slowly from his hiding place. "If that's all that guy came here for," he mused, "why did he act so leery of being seen?"\par
The next moment the Indian lighted a cigarette. After a few puffs he stamped it out and started back for the crafts building.\par
Joe grinned as he recalled a \i No Smoking \i0 sign in the building.\par
"So he just slipped out to have a smoke. He sure had me fooled."\par
Joe started walking back toward the village. Suddenly he stopped in his tracks. What was that strange scraping noise behind him off to the right?\par
He stealthily retraced his steps in the direction of the sound, which led him to a small clearing. Joe barely restrained an exclamation when he saw a man digging in the hard-packed earth.\par
It was the stranger in the suede-fringed suit whom the boys had met the day before!\par
Without hesitation, Joe approached the digger.\par
"Now I'll find out what his game is," he was thinking when a twig snapped behind him.\par
Joe looked over his shoulder in time to see a man leaping toward him, brandishing a stick.\par
He tried to duck, but the man brought the stick smashing down on the boy's head.\par
Without uttering a cry, Joe crumpled to the earth!\par
\par
\par
CHAPTER XII\line\b\i A Puzzling Telegram\par
\i0\par
\b0 A QUARTER of an hour passed before Joe stirred. Opening his eyes, he was conscious only of a severe pain in the top of his head. Feeling the damp earth against his cheek, the young detective realized he was lying on the ground.\par
With what seemed like a superhuman effort, Joe lifted himself on one elbow and saw the trees about him. Only then did he remember what had occurred. He put his hand to his head and felt a large bump.\par
"I'd better get back to the Ramapan village," he muttered. "Got to warn Chief Whitestone about those men."\par
His head throbbed. Swaying from side to side, Joe took a few uncertain steps. It was hard going but finally he reached the edge of the village. There he saw a familiar figure hurrying up the street.\par
"Chet!" He tried to shout, but his words were barely audible and his friend turned a corner out of sight. Joe started for the Whitestone house, stopping frequently to rest.\par
Suddenly he heard a cry behind him. "Joe! What happened?"\par
"Ted! Oh, gosh, I'm glad to see you."\par
"Who hit you?" Ted exclaimed, seeing a huge, bloody lump on the top of Joe's head.\par
"Don't know," he gasped as the Indian boy steered him toward his house.\par
As they reached the steps, Chief Whitestone came out. He helped Ted lift Joe and soon the injured youth was resting on a couch.\par
Ted hurried for the village doctor. After a thorough examination the physician concluded that there was no skull fracture, but told Joe that he might have a headache for a few hours and to call him if anything else developed. He dressed the wound and left.\par
A sigh escaped Ted's lips. "Thought you were a goner when I saw you staggering down that street, Joe," he said, and smiled in relief.\par
But Chief Whitestone was not smiling.\par
"That fellow tried to kill you!" he exclaimed. He clenched his pipe, the knuckles showing white against the dark bowl.\par
"Ted," he went on, "I'm very much concerned about this business. I want you to make inquiries around the village while Joe takes it easy."\par
"Don't worry about me, Chief Whitestone," Joe insisted. "We detectives are used to some roughing up now and then."\par
"Did you get a good look at the man who hit you?" Ted wanted to know.\par
"Yes. But I've never seen him before. I couldn't identify him," Joe said ruefully.\par
At that moment Chet hurried in, having heard from a child that the doctor had been calling on "the sick white boy."\par
"Joe!" he exclaimed, pale with fright. "What happened?"\par
While Chet was listening to Joe's story, Frank Hardy strode briskly down the forest trail and finally reached Lantern Junction, He went at once to the Grand Hotel.\par
"We're moving out," he told the pleasant clerk.\par
"Going home so soon?"\par
"No. We're staying with the Ramapans. If any messages come here, we'll pay to have them delivered up there in care of the chief."\par
"Glad to oblige you," the clerk said.\par
After paying the bill, packing, and arranging for all the bags but one to be checked at the hotel, Frank decided to telephone his mother.\par
She herself answered. "Frank? What a relief to hear from you!"\par
"Anything wrong?" he wanted to know, detecting a note of agitation in Mrs. Hardy's voice.\par
"Yes. I was afraid those men might have been after you and Joe again. There's been another attempted burglary of our house!"\par
Frank grabbed at the mouthpiece. "Are you and Aunt Gertrude all right? Did you see the burglar? Did he get anything?"\par
"We're all right," Mrs. Hardy replied quickly. "But the burglar got away. I can't tell you whether he stole anything or not. Chief Collig is working on the case right now.\par
"There's more news of your father," his mother went on.\par
"Is it good news?"\par
"Well, I don't know. Another case of sabotage," Mrs. Hardy told him. "This time in St. Louis. A laboratory was swept by flames last night and the reports of secret experiments went up in smoke. Dad was reported on the scene."\par
"Good!" Frank exclaimed. "At least the investigation's in capable hands."\par
"But I'm worried, son. I tried to get in touch with your father in St. Louis through the police, but the authorities there told me he had disappeared."\par
"Disappeared!" Frank repeated anxiously, then said, "Maybe he's only gone underground to track down the gang."\par
"I don't know what to think, Frank," Mrs. Hardy replied. "Just a little while ago I got a message that has me completely baffled."\par
"Message from Dad?"\par
"Yes. And it came from California! All the telegram said was \i 'Detained in California. Will wire again.'"\i0\par
"But the report of the sabotage placed Dad in St. Louis."\par
"Exactly." Mrs. Hardy sighed. "I think the wire from California is a hoax!"\par
"Something's fishy, that's sure," Frank agreed. "But don't worry. I have an idea. I'll let you know when I learn something."\par
"All right, dear, and give my love to Joe."\par
Frank clicked the phone, then asked the operator to connect him with John Bryant in San Francisco. The man was a detective friend of Fen-ton Hardy and could be depended upon.\par
"Hello, Frank. Glad to hear from you. Great things your father's doing these days."\par
"That's why I'm calling. We're worried about reports that he's in two places at once."\par
Mr. Bryant chuckled. "I didn't think even a Hardy could do that."\par
Frank quickly explained the mystery of his father's seemingly double appearances.\par
"This is my plan," he said, speaking guardedly. "Will you check on Dad at his hotel, and then wire the result to Sam Radley at the Bayport Hospital? It's important that you send the message to Sam. One to us would probably be intercepted or tampered with. Mother's been getting some, but she thinks they may be phonies."\par
Assuring Frank of his fullest cooperation, Mr. Bryant said good-by.\par
"I'd better warn Sam Radley to expect a message from Mr. Bryant," Frank thought, and hurried to a writing desk.\par
After penning a few lines to his father's injured operative, Frank folded the paper and inserted it in an envelope which he addressed in plain block letters to disguise his handwriting. He sealed the envelope, stamped it, and deposited the letter in a mailbox at the end of the lobby.\par
"Nobody will dare tamper with Uncle Sam's mails," he told himself in satisfaction.\par
Waving to the desk clerk, Frank walked out of the hotel with his suitcase. As he turned down the street that led to the Ramapan trail, he saw a familiar figure hurrying toward him. It was Chet Morton!\par
Frank ran to meet Chet, who was gasping for breath from his exertions.\par
"Raced most of the way," he panted, "to tell you about-about Joe. Attacked by stranger- knocked out!" Chet heaved as he tried to regain his wind.\par
"Knocked out! By whom? Tell me!" Frank shook Chet in his excitement.\par
Sitting down on the curb, and pausing frequently to get his breath, Chet recounted Joe's experience in the woods.\par
"The doctor's seen him. He'll be okay. I came to town for the police."\par
"Go on," Frank urged.\par
Chet arose, his breathing restored. "Ted and I went to find Joe's attacker," he said.\par
"Any luck?" Frank asked. He was seething at the thought of his brother's being brutally assaulted.\par
"We located the spot where the man attacked Joe," Chet replied, "and searched the area. Finally we saw tracks leading to the main trail and followed them for a few yards until they were lost."\par
"Did you find any other clue?" Frank asked, disappointed that they had not caught Joe's assailant.\par
Chet grinned in satisfaction. "We found this."\par
Digging inside his jacket, he produced a package wrapped in cloth.\par
"What is it?" Frank asked, puzzled.\par
Chet unwrapped the cloth. "A piece of the stick used on Joe!"\par
"Good work, Chet!" Frank cried.\par
Carefully he examined the piece. One end was splintered, showing that it had been broken by a violent blow.\par
"You're taking this to the police?" he asked.\par
"Sure. For fingerprints!"\par
The boys went at once. Frank gave the desk sergeant their names and asked for the chief. The visitors were ushered into his office.\par
"Frank Hardy, eh?" he greeted them. He was a short, plump man, who gave the boys a warm smile and told them to call him Mike. "Any relation to Fenton Hardy, the famous detective?"\par
"His son. My brother's at the Ramapan village."\par
"Well, well," the officer said. "What brings you boys up to this neck of the woods? Some mystery?"\par
Quickly Frank explained their mission to find a thief named Breck. When he told the officer what had happened to Joe, the police chief looked grave.\par
"Any clues?" he asked.\par
Chet produced the stick and told about finding it near the spot where Joe had been attacked.\par
"I thought the fellow's fingerprints might be on it," he added hopefully.\par
"It won't take long to find out," Mike replied, then carried the piece of wood into a back room.\par
While he was gone, the boys talked over the various aspects of the mystery, and Frank whispered the latest news about his father.\par
"Good night!" Chet exclaimed.\par
A short while later the officer returned, a satisfied look on his face. In one hand he carried a Manila folder.\par
"Well, Chet," he said, "you hit the jackpot. We found a jailbird's fingerprints on this stick!"\par
A broad grin broke over the boy's face. Frank congratulated him.\par
"Whose prints are they?" he asked.\par
Mike opened the folder and took out some papers. "Fellow by the name of Smirkis," he told them. "About forty years old. Small-time crook. Got a year for robbery some months back. He was released a short time ago for good behavior. Lives right here in town."\par
"Smirkis, eh?" Frank mused. "I wonder if he's connected with the gang we're after."\par
"I couldn't say. He wasn't too bad a fellow, but he may have met someone in prison who put ideas in his head," Mike said.\par
"Where does he live?" Frank asked.\par
"We just checked with the landlady of his rooming house, but she said he hasn't been home in a couple of days. I've sent out an alarm for him.\par
"We'll need your brother to identify Smirkis as the assailant when we catch up with him. Meanwhile, take care of yourselves," Mike warned.\par
The boys thanked him, ate a light lunch, and then headed back to the Indian village. Frank was anxious to see Joe and was glad to find him feeling better.\par
Next day, while Joe was recuperating, he discussed the clue to the missing papers and the jeweled dagger with Frank, Chet, and Ted. Chief Whitestone had gone to Lantern Junction on business.\par
" 'Buried where a crisscross shadow is cast in the light of the hunter's moon,' " Chet mulled over the chief's statement. "Wonder what made the crisscross shadow."\par
He and Joe made several suggestions that were immediately discounted by Ted because they did not jibe with the legend.\par
"The story goes this way. 'And the chief buried the dagger of the many bright eyes and the papers of the paleface writing while at his hunter's dwelling in the early moonrise.' "\par
"Hunter's dwelling!" Frank cried. "I have it!"\par
\par
\par
CHAPTER XIII\line\b\i The Hunters Moon\par
\i0\par
\b0 "WHAT?" Joe, Chet, and Ted chorused in surprise.\par
"A hunter's dwelling," Frank explained, "could be a teepee. The crisscross shadow was made by the poles I"\par
"Of course!" Ted exclaimed. "Why didn't we Ramapans think of that?"\par
"And the hunter's moon is in October, isn't it?" Chet asked.\par
"Yes, it's the full moon of October and it rises early just like the legend says," Ted answered. "In October the angle the moon makes with the earth is very slight, so it rises as the full moon very soon after sunset."\par
"We're going into the hunter's moon right now," Frank said. "That's what your father meant, Ted, when he urged us to solve the mystery soon!"\par
"Yes."\par
"First thing to do," Frank went on, "is to find out where the chief's teepee stood when he buried the treasure. Have you any idea where that was?" he asked Ted.\par
"It was near where the tribe used to hold its ceremonials," Ted replied. "The records say that the ceremonial rock was located where a stream, forked like a serpent's tongue, cuts through the warrior's place of honor."\par
"What does that mean?" Chet questioned.\par
"Long ago, returning warriors were honored for a whole day by feasting and-"\par
"Sounds good." The stout boy beamed. "They probably had roast moose and-"\par
"Let's get going," Frank interrupted.\par
Ted led the way to the area where the old ceremonials had been held. He said that it had not been used in his lifetime.\par
"Then we're going to have a hard job locating the rock in this overgrown tangle," Joe remarked, looking around.\par
He had insisted upon going along but the others made him sit on the side lines and not exert himself. Disgusted, Joe sat down on a log which had fallen across what once had been the fork in the stream mentioned in the legend.\par
"Looks as if we're stumped," he said ten minutes later when the boys found no evidence of a large flat rock.\par
Frank, who had squatted down near him and was staring in the direction of the main stream, suddenly gave a shout.\par
"There it is, fellows!"\par
He ran toward a little mound of silt and moss that they had overlooked in their search. Digging excitedly for a few seconds, and scraping away the incrustation of many years, he exposed a huge, flat rock to the light.\par
"And now to find out where the chief's teepee stood," Joe said.\par
"It's beyond me," Chet commented, and wearily sat down on the rock.\par
"Paleface boy want to know where old chief's teepee stood?" a voice behind him said.\par
Chet jumped in surprise and whirled to look at an elderly Indian wearing a leather shirt and leggings.\par
"Hello, Long Heart," Ted greeted the old man.\par
The boys had seen him around the village, dressed in the outmoded costume of the Ramapans. Ted introduced him as the oldest member of the tribe.\par
"He's always telling us stories of the old days," Ted said, smiling.\par
"We do want to know where the old chief's teepee stood," Frank said. "Can you help us?"\par
"My memory not so good-for I am many moons old," Long Heart answered. "But maybe remember where teepee of great brave stood."\par
With that, he started walking back and forth, muttering to himself. Finally he stopped two hundred feet from the ceremonial rock.\par
"Here," he said with finality. "Here teepee of chief. Why paleface want know this?" he asked Ted suspiciously.\par
After the boy told him the palefaces were trying to find the lost deed in order to save the tribe's land, the old brave's eyes lighted up.\par
"Me help," he said simply. "You build teepee with pole fifteen feet long. Me come tonight at rise of moon." Saying no more, he turned his back and went toward the village.\par
"How do you build a Ramapan teepee?" Chet asked. "Is it any different from the ones we made at camp?"\par
"Probably not." Ted grinned. "I guess you palefaces learned how from us Indians."\par
Nevertheless, he instructed them as they began their work. They cut down six saplings fifteen feet long and tied them together three feet from the top. Then they raised the poles and spread the legs to form a firm base, pressing them into the ground.\par
The next step was to lash short, flexible saplings horizontally across the slanting poles. After that, they fastened sections of birch and hemlock bark over them with tough vines and trailing roots. Short poles were used to cover the bark to keep it from curling.\par
Finally they cut a smoke hole at the top and another for an entrance. The boys stood back proudly to view their work.\par
"Pretty swell," Chet remarked. "Now if that old moon'll just come out, we'll find that deed for your dad in no time, Ted," he boasted.\par
"I suppose it's expecting too much to keep this operation a secret from our enemies," Frank remarked. "But let's come here separately tonight and watch for any spies."\par
"Agreed," they all said.\par
Just before sunset the Hardys, Chet, Ted, and Chief Whitestone, going by separate routes, arrived at the old ceremonial rock. They found Long Heart waiting impassively for them.\par
"The weather's holding up," Frank said to Joe.\par
Slowly the sun sank below the horizon. Then a few minutes later the hunter's moon of the legend shone from behind some clouds. Eagerly six pairs of eyes followed the clouds until they blew away.\par
Suddenly Joe whispered excitedly, "There it is -the crisscross shadow!"\par
It was true. The poles atop the teepee made crisscrossed shadows on the moonlit ground.\par
"Let's dig!" Ted cried, grasping one of the shovels they had brought along.\par
With grim determination the group sank their spades into the earth and started working.\par
Would they uncover the missing papers and the jeweled dagger? each one wondered, the silent chief most of all.\par
The mound of earth beside the hole swiftly grew higher as the pit widened and deepened under the eager labors of the treasure hunters.\par
Finally Frank paused and leaned on his shovel. "Whew!" he said. "It may be cold by the thermometer, but I'm sure hot."\par
"Me too," Chet puffed. "This digging is getting harder the farther down we go." He stood in a wide hole up to his knees.\par
"It's very rocky in this country," Chief White-stone remarked.\par
After a rest, the four plunged their spades into the hard-packed earth with renewed vigor. The bright hunter's moon cast an eerie light over the scene, with stalwart Long Heart standing guard.\par
Joe, regretting that he was not in condition to help the others, stationed himself in the shadow of the teepee, keeping alert for any intruder-accidental or planned.\par
Suddenly he tensed. He strained his ears to catch a sound over the hard breathing of his friends and the soft thuds the earth made as it was shoveled from the pit. The sound came again.\par
"A twig being stepped on in the woods," Joe told himself. "I'd better have a look!"\par
Quietly he slipped among the trees from which the mysterious crackling had come. Joe peered through the maze of moonlight and shadows.\par
Ahead he thought he could detect a man moving silently among the trees!\par
He tried to follow the ghostly figure. But it kept eluding him and finally disappeared. Wondering who it could have been, Joe retraced his steps to the clearing where the others were still working.\par
"Find anything yet?" Joe called out\par
Chief Whitestone tossed his shovel aside and clambered out of the hole. The others followed.\par
"Not a thing!" he replied to Joe.\par
"We're getting no place here," Frank said. "I guess it's useless to dig any more. There are certainly no buried papers in this spot."\par
"Looks as if you're right," Ted agreed. "I guess we had the wrong spot for the teepee, or the wrong crisscross shadow."\par
In the moonlight the disappointment on everyone's face was easily seen.\par
"Buck up, fellows," Joe said encouragingly. "Maybe after a good night's sleep we can figure out where we failed to interpret the clue in the legend correctly."\par
"Right you are, Joe," the chief said. "Let's return home. We'll all have hot drinks, then go straight to bed."\par
As the others gathered up their tools, Joe took Frank aside. Swiftly he told him of the incident in the woods, and his suspicions that the group had been spied upon by a prowler.\par
"No use worrying the others about it," he said. "Listen! Let's stay overnight in the teepee and keep watch for intruders."\par
"Great idea," Frank agreed. "The teepee's weathertight, and we'll bring some blankets."\par
Chief Whitestone and Ted protested strongly when they heard the plan, but the Hardys insisted.\par
As the others trooped slowly out of the clearing back to the village, Frank glanced at the moon. "Look!" he pointed. "Clouds up there. Bad weather ahead."\par
"Let's hurry and get things ready for the night," Joe suggested. "We'll need a fire."\par
Quickly they gathered dead pine limbs and brush and in a short while had a small, cheerful fire blazing inside the teepee. Chet returned with several blankets, then said good night.\par
As the boys finished adjusting the bark door, Joe held out his hand. "Snow," he said. "Well, I'll take the first watch. You get some sleep."\par
In a few moments Frank's regular breathing indicated he was asleep. Bundling warmly, Joe took up his guard duty. The early snow began falling more thickly. After a couple of hours, he woke his brother.\par
"How's the weather?" Frank asked.\par
"Snowing pretty hard. Nothing stirring out there. But keep your eyes open," he warned.\par
During Frank's watch the snow gradually turned to fine rain, but by the time he changed watches, it had stopped.\par
"Starting to turn mighty cold out there," he said as Joe took up his post.\par
Morning finally came. The temperature was way down, and when the dawn broke, the clearing and the woods were covered with a dazzling glaze of ice.\par
There was a rustling at the bark door to the teepee and Ted poked his head through the opening.\par
"Good morning, fellows. Anything happen during the night?"\par
"Not a thing," Frank replied.\par
But Joe was staring intently at a man who was emerging stealthily from the underbrush. As the stranger reached the clearing, Joe cried out in startled recognition:\par
"That's my attacker!"\par
With a leap, he charged the mysterious fellow and tripped him.\par
"Good going!" Frank cried.\par
In a moment Ted pinned his hands behind his back, and the man was their prisoner.\par
"You're the guy who whacked me-Smirkis!" Joe said accusingly.\par
"All right, I'm Smirkis. But I never whacked any of you," the man protested.\par
"No? Well, your fingerprints were on the stick. What's more, I saw you sneaking around while we were digging last night!"\par
"No, I didn't spy on you." Smirkis shook his head vigorously, but he had paled at Joe's mention of the fingerprints.\par
"You'd better come with us to police headquarters," Frank said.\par
"Wait a minute!" Smirkis cried out anxiously. "I'll make a deal with you."\par
"What kind of deal?" Joe asked.\par
"If you'll let me go, I'll give you some vital information. How about it?" he whined.\par
The boys looked at one another questioningly. It was attractive bait that Smirkis was offering. His vital information might lead to the solution of the mystery!\par
Joe and Frank moved out of the man's hearing to talk it over. "I don't trust him," Joe whispered.\par
Frank nodded. "Let's try to trick him."\par
He turned to Smirkis. "I know what you're going to tell us. That the men who want to buy this property hired you to get rid of us!"\par
"How'd you know that?" Smirkis gasped.\par
No sooner had he uttered the words than a strange voice behind them cried, "Shut up!"\par
Frank and Joe wheeled around to face three masked men, poised to attack!\par
\par
\par
CHAPTER XIV\line\b\i A Rough Trip\par
\i0\par
\b0 As the Hardys leaped at their attackers, one of the masked men side-stepped them to clamp a hand over Ted's mouth as he started to give the Ramapan war cry for help. Locked in a fierce struggle, Joe and Frank hurled their opponents to the ground. The boys fought with every bit of strength they could muster, but the odds were against them.\par
"Okay, tie 'em up and blindfold 'em," ordered one of the men, who seemed to be the leader.\par
The arms of the young detectives and their Indian friend were tightly bound and their eyes covered with kerchiefs.\par
"All set?" the same voice asked. "Let's go! You know the plan, men."\par
Frank and Joe were roughly grasped by the shoulders and pushed.\par
"Start walking," the leader ordered.\par
As they trudged off, the Hardys heard sounds heading in another direction.\par
"They're separating us from Ted," Joe whispered to Frank.\par
"Keep quiet!" the leader commanded.\par
"You won't be so anxious to stick your noses in other people's business when we get through with you," one of the men sneered.\par
"You can't win, anyway," the leader said. "In a short while the Indians will be gone!"\par
"You're trying to bluff us," Frank spoke up boldly.\par
"Bluffing, you say? Just wait and see. This land's going to change hands, and you can't stop it!"\par
After a long silence, one of the men said, "What about Smirkis? He talks too much!"\par
"The boss'll take care of him after he does that job for us."\par
So Smirkis was the one who had taken Ted away!\par
Presently the boys were halted. Then hands lifted them up and lowered them into a canoe.\par
"Okay," the leader said. "Let's shove off."\par
After a silent trip of an hour or so the bottom of the canoe scraped against sand, and in a moment the boys were jerked to their feet and dragged across the ground. Next, they were lifted into a vehicle with its engine running. They started off over a rough road.\par
Joe and Frank were ravenous, not having eaten for many hours, but the men made no offer of food. The car rumbled on for what seemed an eternity.\par
"We must be a long way from the Ramapans by now!" Frank thought. "Where are we going?"\par
Almost an hour later the car stopped. The prisoners were hauled out. The wind was blowing in gusts as if a storm were brewing.\par
"What next?" the Hardys thought, then heard a plane's motor being tuned up. They were hoisted into the craft and it took off.\par
Judging by the way they were being jounced in the air, Frank and Joe realized that they had been stowed in the tail section.\par
It was a rough trip, with no chance for them to try to loosen their bonds. The plane rose and fell with dizzying speed as it was buffeted by the wind. The drumming of hail indicated that the storm was becoming more violent, and the swift changes of pressure on their eardrums were sickening.\par
When the plane finally landed, the prisoners were gagged. Then they were carried out, thrown into a car, and driven a distance. After a while the car halted and the boys were pushed up a flight of stairs.\par
"Okay," the leader ordered curtly, "cover your own faces and then take off their blindfolds."\par
The Hardys blinked as the light, though dim, struck their eyes. Peering around, they found themselves in a gloomy, shabbily furnished room. Their masked captors surrounded them menacingly.\par
Suddenly the young detectives caught sight of a transparent curtain near one end of the room. A figure was seated behind it, half turned toward them.\par
The boys gasped. "Dad!" they cried out, shocked by what they saw.\par
Mr. Hardy looked badly mauled and mistreated. His clothes were mussed and dirt-streaked. His head hung in an attitude of complete defeat!\par
The masked leader addressed the boys. "You've been wondering about your father. Now you know. Mr. Hardy, your sons are here. Speak to them."\par
"Boys," he said, without moving, "you can't beat these men. Give up!"\par
Astonished, Frank and Joe tried to break loose and rush to him. But quickly the strong hands of their captors reached out and halted them. They were whisked into an adjoining room and flung violently onto the floor.\par
Their blindfolds were replaced and tape was fastened over their lips in place of the gags.\par
"That ought to hold you," the leader snarled as they struggled in vain, "until you go on your next trip."\par
The boys wondered what he meant, and an explanation was immediately forthcoming.\par
"We'll be back to put you on a freighter," he went on, "and when it reaches its destination, you won't be in a position to bother anybody!"\par
The door slammed and footfalls told the Hardys that the men had gone. After waiting to make sure that a guard had not been posted, they struggled with their bonds, grunting and panting behind their sealed lips. But their captors had done their work well. The ropes would not budge an inch! Exhausted, they sprawled on the floor.\par
Suddenly Frank got an idea. "It might work," he told himself hopefully.\par
Crawling over to Joe, he raised himself erect, using his brother's body as a prop. Slipping his bound wrists over the doorknob, he wriggled his hands round and round.\par
Finally one of the bonds loosened, then another. Frank twisted his hands violently. The ropes slipped. He was free!\par
Quickly he ripped off the blindfold and the adhesive tape, then released his brother.\par
"Thank goodness!" Joe whispered. "Now to break out of here!"\par
Rubbing their chafed wrists, the boys surveyed the dingy little room. The only exit was the door. When it refused to open, Joe said:\par
"Come on. Let's crash it!"\par
Rearing back, they heaved against the door.\par
Once, twice, then a loud splintering noise and the door gave way.\par
Crashing into the other room, they looked for their father. But he as well as the men had vanished!\par
"They've taken Dad with them!" Joe cried.\par
"Come on," Frank urged. "Let's get out of here. We have work to do to save him!"\par
The boys dashed down the stairs and into the street. They gazed around them.\par
"This place looks familiar," Frank said, then added excitedly as he saw a store sign, "We're in Southport!"\par
"Let's get to the police fast, Frank," Joe urged, "before those men get too far away with Dad!"\par
"Hold on a minute!" Frank exclaimed, a strange look coming over his face. "There's something mighty queer about this whole deal. Before we see the police, I suggest that we get in touch with Mother and with Sam Radley."\par
"You suspect something?" Joe asked.\par
"I sure do!"\par
\par
\par
CHAPTER XV\line\b\i The Hideout\par
\i0\par
\b0 "THAT wasn't Dad at all," Frank told Joe.\par
"What!"\par
"Bet you anything! He'd have given us some sign."\par
"But it was his voice," Joe protested.\par
"That's the only part which puzzles me," Frank confessed. "Before we go to the police, let's check with Sam Radley and find out whether he's heard from Mr. Bryant."\par
"Good idea. But how about some food?"\par
"You find a taxi and I'll grab some sandwiches."\par
"With what?" Joe asked.\par
Frank realized ruefully that they did not have any money and knew no one in town but the police.\par
"I guess we'll have to go to them after all and borrow some money."\par
They walked to headquarters and told their story. The captain said he would investigate the place at once. By the time the boys had washed, combed their hair, and brushed their clothes, the officers had returned. They reported that they could find no trace of the kidnappers.\par
"I'm sure they won't return," the captain commented, adding that Breck and York had not been seen in Southport.\par
The boys asked for a loan of ten dollars, then left. Munching sandwiches and drinking soda on their way in the taxi, they soon reached the Bayport Hospital.\par
Sam Radley was lying in bed reading. He looked up over the top of the paper.\par
"Why, hello, Frank and Joe. Where'd you come from?" the detective asked in astonishment.\par
"It's a long story," Frank replied. He briefly outlined their adventures, ending with his suspicion that the man at Southport was not Mr. Hardy.\par
"You could be right," Sam conceded. "Here's a telegram from Mr. Bryant." The message read:\par
\b STOP WORRYING AROUT YOUR BOSS.\b0\par
"That practically proves the man in Southport wasn't Dad," Frank said.\par
"Not necessarily," Sam replied. "It's just possible your father allowed himself to be captured on purpose to get closer to the gang and its operations."\par
"But why did he warn us to lay off?" Joe asked.\par
"For two reasons: so you wouldn't get hurt, and also so you wouldn't interfere with his sleuthing."\par
"That might be, but I still don't believe the man we saw in Southport was Dad."\par
"I don't agree with you, Frank," his brother declared. "I'm sure even an actor couldn't imitate Dad's voice so perfectly."\par
A gong sounded, and a nurse appeared. "Visitors must leave now," she said, and to be sure they did, she waited until the boys bid Sam good night and hurried down the corridor.\par
When they reached their home, Joe suddenly grinned. "Mother and Aunt Gertrude will certainly be surprised to see us. They think that we're still up in the mountains."\par
"Who's there?" a suspicious voice called from behind the door.\par
"It's us, Aunt Gertrude," Frank answered.\par
The door swung open wide. "Joe! Frank!" she cried. "I'm glad you're home!"\par
"Who's there?" Mrs. Hardy asked, coming to the hallway. "My boys!" she exclaimed, hugging them.\par
The reason for their sudden appearance was soon told. The women's eyes widened in amazement, and they asked them not to return to the dangerous area.\par
"But we don't know what happened to Ted Whitestone!" Joe said. "He may be a prisoner."\par
"I understand," Mrs. Hardy replied. "How about telephoning his father?"\par
"We'll do that, anyway," Frank said. "But if we're going to solve the Ramapan mystery, we must work before the hunter's moon is gone."\par
When he talked to Chief Whitestone, the man said a search had already been started for all three boys. He was amazed to hear what had happened, and was glad that the Hardys had escaped. The chief said grimly he would notify the police about Smirkis and the other men and that efforts to find his son would be redoubled.\par
"We'll be back as soon as we can," Frank promised.\par
"That's fine, but I'm afraid Ted is miles away by this time," his father said woefully.\par
Joe called the airport and learned that a plane which left Bayport early in the morning stopped at Lantern Junction. He quickly made reservations.\par
Meanwhile, Frank had begun to worry about the safety of his mother and Aunt Gertrude. He was afraid that when the gang found out the boys had escaped they might come to the Hardy home and seek revenge.\par
"I'm going to ask Chief Collig to post plainclothesmen at the house day and night," he said, and dialed the police headquarters.\par
Collig was not there, but he left the message with the sergeant who promised cooperation.\par
"A man will be here in a few minutes," Frank reported to his family.\par
He and Joe set an alarm clock and tumbled into bed. The next morning they found it hard to awaken when the buzzer sounded, but they got up and dressed quickly. After kissing their aunt and mother good-by, the boys left the house. They stopped for a moment to talk with the detective on guard, then started for the airport.\par
Arriving just in time, the Hardys took their seats in the small plane that serviced the mountainous region of the Ramapan country. An hour later they landed near Lantern Junction and were driven to town. After a hearty breakfast at the Grand Hotel they set out once more for the Indian village.\par
"We'd better keep our eyes open for anybody lying in wait for us," Frank advised. "I'll lead off and look in front and to the right. You check what's on our left and in back of us."\par
But they saw no one and reached the Ramapan village without incident. When Chief Whitestone opened the door he grasped their hands eagerly.\par
"You're back! But there's no word of Ted! You have no idea where he might be?"\par
"I'm afraid, Chief Whitestone," Frank said, "that he's a prisoner of the people who are trying to get your land away from you."\par
The Indian stared unbelievingly. "You mean they're holding him as a hostage?"\par
"Probably."\par
"I had no idea what danger you'd get into when I asked you to find the deed," the chief said. "We've looked in vain for Ted so far. Chet and some of the villagers as well as the police are out now hunting for him. Have you anything to suggest?"\par
The boys said they were so sure that Smirkis was holding Ted prisoner, they would base their efforts on that assumption.\par
"Let's phone Mike right away," said Frank.\par
He dashed to the telephone. Seconds later he realized that the wire was dead.\par
"More of the gang's work," Frank said in disgust. "They cut the line!"\par
Joe suggested that he and Frank hurry to town and tell their story to the police. Without waiting for Chet, they returned to Lantern Junction and went to headquarters.\par
"We think Ted was taken away by Smirkis," Joe said. "Can you tell us anything about his haunts so we can look for him too?"\par
Mike ran his fingers through his hair before replying. Suddenly he snapped his fingers.\par
"The cabin!" he exclaimed. "That's the place. It just came to me. Smirkis once had a hunting cabin in the woods. He sold it, but I'll bet that's where he's hiding."\par
The Hardys were on their feet in an instant. "Come on!" said Frank. "Let's have a look right away!"\par
The officer got his car and they drove a couple of miles out of town. Mike parked and they started off through a heavily overgrown area.\par
After a twenty-minute trek Mike suddenly held up his hand and motioned them to be quiet.\par
"It's just through those trees," he said, pointing.\par
Treading carefully the three moved silently toward the cabin. There was no sign of life.\par
Joe ducked down and moved to a spot underneath a window. The others followed. Raising their heads, they peered inside.\par
In the dusky room they could see nothing at first, then suddenly each received a shock.\par
\i Ted Whitestone was trussed up and propped against the wall!\par
\par
\i0\par
CHAPTER XVI\line\b\i A Moonlight Search\par
\i0\par
\b0 SMIRKIS was standing in front of Ted, a whip held menacingly in one hand.\par
"You'd better tell me!" he snarled. "If you don't, you'll get more of this whip!"\par
"You can't get me to talk by torture!" Ted answered defiantly.\par
The onlookers could see several ugly welts on the boy's arms.\par
"Where's that buried treasure?" Smirkis demanded, using the whip on the boy's hands. "You know all right, but you and your father are trying to keep it for yourselves!"\par
Mike signaled the Hardys. "Okay," he whispered. "Time to move! Circle the cabin!"\par
Frank and Joe took strategic positions so Smirkis could not escape. Then, with a tremendous crash, Mike assailed the door and burst into the room!\par
The police officer dived for Smirkis. Though taken off guard, the wily swindler was not to be caught so easily. He slashed at his opponent with the whip, then leaped through a window.\par
But he was trapped. Frank and Joe converged on him from either side.\par
"Okay. I give up, but I can explain everything," the man declared as they led him into the cabin.\par
Meanwhile, Mike was releasing Ted from his bonds. The Hardys turned their prisoner over to the police officer and rushed up to Ted.\par
"It's sure good to see you fellows," the Indian boy said, chafing his wrists where the ropes had been fastened.\par
"Are you all right?" Frank asked.\par
"I guess you just got here in time," Ted replied soberly. Then they all turned their attention to Smirkis.\par
"You'd better come clean," Mike told him. "Who's paying you and what do they want?"\par
Smirkis hung his head. "A stranger hired me.'*\par
"What was his name?"\par
"He didn't tell me. He just said, 'Call me Al. I'll pay you well.' "\par
"For what?"\par
"To spy on the Ramapans. He said they had a fabulous buried treasure."\par
"A spy, eh?" Frank broke in. "Find out anything?"\par
"No," Smirkis muttered.\par
The Hardys wondered if he were speaking the truth.\par
"Where is this Al now?" Joe asked.\par
The prisoner shrugged.\par
"Where did he stay when he was in town?" Mike prodded him.\par
Smirkis looked at his captors sheepishly. "I let him stay in this cabin. I knew the owner wouldn't come here. Al told me he couldn't be seen in town."\par
"Wanted, eh?" the officer remarked.\par
"What did Al look like?" Frank asked.\par
"He's a dark, heavy-set man. About thirty-five, I'd say. He has a bad scar on the back of his right hand. Looks like a W."\par
"Breck!" Joe exclaimed. "Boy, does that explain a lot!"\par
"Good work!" the police officer said admiringly to the Hardys. "This Al or Breck-whatever his name is-we'll set a watch on this cabin, and if he shows up, we'll bring him in."\par
Mike took the prisoner back to town, and the boys set out for the Ramapan village.\par
"Did that guy talk to you all the time?" Frank asked Ted.\par
"No. He slept a lot, and once he went off for several hours."\par
"To cut the telephone line at your house," Joe deduced.\par
"At first he wasn't bad to me and gave me food regularly. But this morning he started whipping me 'cause I wouldn't talk."\par
Chief Whitestone was relieved to see his son, and Chet bubbled over with joy at seeing all three safe.\par
"This mystery gets more complicated," the chief remarked. "Since you've been gone, I've received a letter from that man you asked me about -Philip York."\par
"Philip York?" the Hardys chorused.\par
"He claims to be the grandson, by a former marriage, of the Amos York who once owned this land. You recall we bought it from his estate."\par
"What did he want?" Frank asked.\par
"He says his father didn't get his share of the money when the property was sold."\par
"Has he any real claim?" Chet put in.\par
"If he has, we're in trouble," Chief Whitestone replied, "because all heirs have to be accounted for when any land is sold."\par
"Didn't the lawyers know about him?" Joe wanted to know.\par
"Philip York claims his father knew nothing about the deal. If that's true, then the sale of the property was illegal and the transaction has to be made all over again."\par
"Whew!" Joe whistled. "And you'd have to pay anything extra they might ask?"\par
"Yes," the chief said, frowning. "York claims he has half brothers and sisters to be paid in addition. They could insist we give them a small fortune to sign off. And we just haven't got the money."\par
There was silence for a few moments, then Chief Whitestone continued. "The second thing I'm worried about is a little closer to home."\par
"What is it?" Frank asked anxiously.\par
"Someone has been digging around the spot where we were looking for the buried treasure!"\par
"When did you discover it?" Joe questioned.\par
"I found bootmarks and freshly turned earth this morning, which means someone must have been there last night."\par
The boys gasped. "I wonder if the digger found anything!" Ted exclaimed.\par
Chief Whitestone tapped his pipe on the table, then replied, "It's hard to tell, Ted. Whoever it was dug quite deep, though."\par
"Father, we must find out whether he was successful!"\par
"But how?" Chief Whitestone asked.\par
Almost immediately Frank came up with a plan. "We'll fool him and use a decoy."\par
"What kind?" Ted asked.\par
"The best decoy in the world," he told them. "The whole Ramapan tribe! They can put on their hunter's moon ceremonial dance this evening instead of waiting."\par
"I see," said Joe. "If the digger didn't find the treasure, he'll be back."\par
"Exactly. While everyone is watching the dance, he'll count on being alone. But you and I, Joe, will keep watch by the teepee."\par
"Great idea, Frank," Chief Whitestone responded, slapping the youth on the back. "I'll get the preparations for the ceremonial dance started right away."\par
"Say," Chet remarked eagerly, "that's really a corker of a plan after all, Frank!"\par
The Hardys became restless as they waited, but finally darkness fell and the brilliant hunter's moon rose like a flaming ball. Under its bright, glowing light the weird ceremony started.\par
First came the beat of the drums, beginning slowly, but growing more insistent. Then the dancers, dressed in war paint and feathers, started their elaborate rhythmical movements. They chanted, leaped, and twisted, as they circled the soaring flames of the great bonfire.\par
The dance soon got into full swing, with Indian faces reflecting the blaze of the fire and the drums pounding wildly. Although the boys found the strange ritual fascinating, Frank finally whispered to his brother:\par
"We'd better go. We have work to do."\par
Walking stealthily they went straight to the place of the crisscross shadow. No one was around. They slipped inside the teepee and waited.\par
Presently Joe peeked out of the opening. For a moment all he could see was the frozen ground and the dark forest trees, still in the silver moonlight. Then he gave a sudden start.\par
"Someone's coming!" he reported excitedly. "Let's grab him!"\par
As the man came nearer, the boys rushed outside. At that moment something whizzed over their heads. A second later a large knife struck the side of the teepee.\par
Frank seized Joe by the shoulders and jerked him to the ground.\par
"That guy is trying to kill us!"\par
Terrified, the boys waited, their faces pressed into the cold earth. Then they heard the sound of running footsteps.\par
Joe stood up. "I guess the knife thrower's gone. Whew! That was a close shave! Well, at least we know the gang hasn't found the treasure yet!"\par
They walked back to the ceremonial dance, but found that the rite had been completed and the members of the tribe were returning home. The chief was talking soberly with a group of elderly men. Joe caught his eye and he came over in a few minutes.\par
Briefly, the boys recounted the experience with the knife thrower.\par
"I'll keep guards posted here day and night," the chief said gravely.\par
He beckoned to a couple of sturdy young men.\par
After a few short commands from their leader, they stationed themselves near the teepee.\par
"I can use a good night's sleep," said Chet, coming up to them. He yawned.\par
The Hardys grinned. "All worn out from dancing" Joe teased. "You should have been dodging daggers as we were."\par
"Wh-wh-what!" Hearing the story, Chet said, "Wow! We'd better cut out this night work."\par
"We will," Frank agreed. "I'm going to phone Sam Radley to find out if he's heard anything from Dad and then hit the hay."\par
He picked up the phone, which had been repaired earlier.\par
"Mr. Sam Radley, please," he said to the hospital operator. "What! He's disappeared! With a broken leg!"\par
Frank hung up and turned around. "Sam vanished from the hospital very mysteriously this morning. Left a check on the bureau for his bill. No one saw him leave."\par
The boys looked at one another in amazement. Then Joe said, "Try his hotel. Maybe he's there."\par
But Sam was not at the hotel and the clerk had not heard from him.\par
"Maybe he's gone after the saboteurs," Chet suggested.\par
"More likely the gang has taken him captive," Joe said worriedly.\par
The three sat lost in thought for several minutes, then Frank said, "I know somebody who might throw some light on his whereabouts."\par
"Who?"\par
"Jack Wayne. Maybe Jack took Sam on a secret plane flight!"\par
"You're right. Let's phone him."\par
Jack Wayne was a close friend of the Hardys. He owned a plane, and often piloted the boys, their father, or Sam on errands when speed and secrecy were needed to crack a case.\par
In a short time Frank was talking to Jack.\par
"W-e-l-l," Jack began, as if reluctant to reply. "I have seen Sam. Flew him on a secret mission to Chicago this afternoon."\par
"Did he give any details?" Frank wanted to know.\par
"He didn't volunteer much information, and he swore me to secrecy. All I can tell you is this: continue your investigations at the Ramapan village, and don't worry about a thing!"\par
Frank repeated the conversation to his brother and Chet.\par
"Continue our work, eh?" Joe said.\par
"But where?" Chet asked. "We've dug at the site of the crisscross shadow for the buried treasure, and all we have to show for it is a big pile of earth!"\par
"We've sure gone deep enough," Joe declared. "You know what I think? That we haven't been digging at the right shadow!"\par
"You've hit the nail on the head." Frank thumped the arm of his chair. "There's only one thing to do. Find the real crisscross shadow. We must do it tonight. If we wait until tomorrow, it may be cloudy. With the moon blotted out, we'll really be stuck."\par
"Count me in!" Chet exclaimed. "I can always catch up on lost sleep later."\par
Ted and Chief Whitestone helped the Hardys in their preparations. Ted wanted to go on the search, but his father forbade this because of his exhausted condition.\par
Finally, equipped with hooks, picks, shovels, rope, and flashlights, the boys started off for the clearing where the teepee stood. When they arrived, Frank surveyed the area in the moonlight.\par
"The crisscross shadow has to be around here somewhere," he stated firmly. "If it wasn't made by teepee poles, then there must be another object which casts a shadow of the same type."\par
Joe pointed to the sheer side of the mountain that rose out of the clearing.\par
"Let's climb up there and have a look," he suggested. "We'll be able to see over a wider expanse from that height, and we may catch something we haven't noticed before."\par
Picking their way carefully up the steep slope, they finally reached the top of the mountain. The boys paused to catch their breath as they surveyed the whole panorama.\par
Their eyes swept back and forth across the scenic view below them. Intently they took in every detail, seeking the sign of the buried treasure.\par
"Nothing here," Frank said. "Let's look on the other side."\par
They walked across the level summit which was barely a hundred feet wide. The far side dropped off in a sheer cliff. Across a narrow ravine rose another steep rocky slope.\par
Suddenly Joe clutched the other boys' arms.\par
"Look!" he cried, his voice rising in excitement. "Down by that crevice in that cliff over there!"\par
\par
