CHAPTER XVII\line\b\i A Parted Rope\par
\i0\par
\b0 "THE crisscross shadow!"\par
"We've found it at last!"\par
"Hurrah!"\par
The three boys stared at a perfect crossed shadow just above a cleft in the rock wall of the mountainside facing them. It was made by two overhanging slender pinnacles of rock.\par
"Wait a minute," Frank said. "We've found the shadow, but it would be suicide to try climbing down to it."\par
"One misstep and we'd be goners." Chet shivered.\par
"We've got to get down there somehow!" Joe said with determination. "The future of the Ramapan tribe depends on the deed to their property! There's a narrow ledge just below us. If we could only-"\par
"Let's try a rope," Frank suggested, uncoiling one he was carrying over his shoulder.\par
He flung the end far out over the edge of the cliff. It wriggled down the stone face. The tossed coil apparently swung to the floor of the ledge, although from where they were standing the end of it was not visible.\par
"Quick! Tie the rope around a tree," Frank called out. "I'll go down first."\par
"Say, whose idea was this treasure hunt?" Chet objected. But as he gave a look downward, he added, "On the other hand, I'd hate to be selfish."\par
The Hardys grinned as Joe securely tied one end of the rope to a large tree trunk. Frank tested it to be sure it would hold; then, clutching it firmly, he let himself over the edge of the cliff and hand over hand started his descent.\par
Reaching the place where he thought the ledge continued under a sharply jutting overhang, he was doomed to disappointment. Instead of a flat surface, there was a pinnacle upon which it would be impossible to land.\par
"It's no use," he called up.\par
The climb back was more difficult. The rope creaked and Joe and Chet feared it might fray apart from the constant rubbing against the rocks and toss Frank into space. But he finally made it and was hauled up the last few feet.\par
"Chet," Frank said, "how about your going back and telling Chief Whitestone what we've found out? He'll certainly want to throw a guard around this place until proper equipment can be brought to get down there. Meanwhile, Joe and I'll keep watch."\par
Chet immediately crossed to the wooded side of the mountain and began to climb down. Hindered by his bulky figure and heavy clothes, he slipped and slid, making a great deal of noise.\par
Rising, Chet started the trek through the woods. Suddenly he halted. He had heard a sound in the brush. The palms of his hands turned clammy as he listened intently. But he did not hear the rustling again.\par
Shrugging his shoulders, though his heart was hammering, Chet walked on, trying to tread as noiselessly as possible. In a moment he heard the sound once more. This time it was directly behind him!\par
As he swung around he was grasped roughly and thrown to the ground. A hand was clapped over his mouth. He struggled violently, but in vain.\par
His masked captors bound and gagged him, then carried him to a large tree.\par
"Okay," one of the attackers said gruffly. "You know what to do with this pest!"\par
"Yeah, but he weighs a ton," another protested as Chet was hoisted up to the first limb.\par
In a few minutes he was tied to the upper part of the tree trunk, out of sight of the ground.\par
"Next we'll take care of those meddling Hardy boys!" the leader declared.\par
When Chet heard the ominous words, he was terror-stricken. As the men moved off, he struggled to free himself, but he could not budge an inch. His heart sank as he realized that he was powerless to warn his friends.\par
In the meantime, Frank and Joe found a spot some fifty feet farther along the mountain where they thought they could get down to the ledge.\par
"Let's try it!" Joe urged. "Maybe we can hop across from there to the side where the shadow is."\par
They tied the rope around a tree.\par
"My turn this time," Joe declared.\par
He went down carefully, landed on the narrow ledge, and calculated the distance to the other side.\par
"Okay, I'll start down," Frank called.\par
When he was within eight feet of the ledge, he felt the rope quiver. He looked up. His blood froze.\par
High above him, silhouetted against the moonlit sky, a masked face peered down at him. Alongside it was a hand holding a knife.\par
"Frank!" Joe cried in horror. "Somebody's going to cut you off!"\par
Frank reached out desperately to save himself, but it was too late. With a single swipe of the knife, the strands were severed.\par
Frank went tumbling through the air!\par
With superhuman effort Joe braced himself and caught Frank as he came hurtling down the cliffside.\par
But for several moments it was nip and tuck between life and death as they swayed and teetered near the rim of the ledge. Then Frank was able to regain his own balance.\par
Near exhaustion, Frank and Joe sat down, oblivious even of the taunts being called down by the man at the top of the cliff. But finally his raucous voice broke in on their thoughts.\par
"Now what are you going to do?" he snarled.\par
Another joined him and jeered at the boys, "You can't go down. You can't go up. You're trapped!"\par
"That's Breck!" Frank whispered excitedly.\par
"And York!" Joe added.\par
"Well, that definitely ties Dad's and our cases together!"\par
"Guess we'll just have to sit it out until help comes," Joe said. "Chet ought to be back soon."\par
But as the minutes passed and none of their friends arrived, the Hardys began to grow uneasy.\par
"Maybe Chet was captured," Joe remarked apprehensively.\par
The thought sobered them still more. Waiting made them nervous and fidgety. Finally Frank stood up.\par
"As long as we're here, let's cross over to the other ledge and look for the hidden papers and the dagger," he suggested.\par
By inching along the narrow strip they came to a place where the leap across was not too hazardous. In a few moments they were on the other side and hurrying to the spot where they had seen the crisscross shadow.\par
Frank chuckled. "Those men on the top of the cliff may think we've escaped."\par
"Let 'em think so! We'll be well screened!"\par
Reaching the place where the two rock pinnacles were casting their shadow in the moonlight against the cliffside, the boys could now see a narrow opening just below it.\par
"The papers are probably hidden in here somewhere," Frank remarked.\par
They took out their flashlights. Shielding the beams from any prying eyes above them, they began to search.\par
The two young detectives went over every inch, of the rocky surface. For several minutes there was only the sound of their boots scraping the floor of the narrow opening. Then suddenly Joe gave a low cry!\par
