CHAPTER XVIII\line\b\i A Perilous Ruse\par
\i0\par
\b0 FRANK pulled a small rusty chest from a miniature cave hidden among the rocks. He turned his flashlight on it.\par
After trying unsuccessfully to open the lock, Joe finally pried off the lid. From inside gleamed a million beams of light.\par
"The jeweled dagger!" he cried excitedly, picking up the fabulous weapon. The handle was studded with rubies, diamonds, and emeralds.\par
"A regular pirate's treasure!" Frank exclaimed.\par
"The papers are here too," Joe said, digging down for a yellowed bundle.\par
"See if the deed is there," Frank told him.\par
Joe opened a legal-looking document. He scanned it rapidly.\par
"This is it, Frank. The deed to the Ramapans' land!"\par
Just then they heard voices.\par
"We'd better hide this again," Frank advised.\par
Joe reached up and replaced the chest. Then quickly the boys scrambled out to the ledge. As they hurried along toward where they had leaped, the voices grew louder.\par
"Frank! Look over there! They're coming down!"\par
Breck and York were dangling on a long rope almost across from where the boys were standing.\par
The Hardys' first thought was to jump across and try to overpower their enemies, but they realized that a fight on the ledge would mean destruction for all of them. Frank and Joe decided to wait and see what the men's intentions were.\par
The pair had removed their masks and were cautiously making their way down the face of the cliff. The boys waited tensely.\par
"Maybe they're going to bargain with us," Joe said hopefully.\par
Frank did not agree, but replied, "We've got to outwit them. Let's try stalling them off until help comes."\par
"How?"\par
"I'm thinking," his brother answered. "We might-"\par
He had no chance to finish his sentence, for at that moment Breck dropped onto the ledge, and his companion followed a moment later. They jumped the span and faced the Hardys menacingly.\par
"Keep your distance, Breck!" Frank warned.\par
The boys had their shoulders to the wall of the ledge, alert for any move their enemies might make.\par
"Don't worry. We're not going to touch you. Well let starvation take care of that."\par
"What we want to know," the other man spoke up, "is where the treasure's buried." He guffawed. "You found the crisscross shadow for us."\par
"What treasure?" Frank asked in a surprised tone of voice.\par
"Don't give us that innocent stuff," Breck growled. "You know where it is and you're going to tell us!"\par
"How about a little exchange of information?" Frank countered. "You give us some, we'll give you some in return."\par
Joe clutched his brother's arm. "You're not going to tell them, are you?" he whispered anxiously.\par
Frank pressed Joe's fingers in a negative signal.\par
"A deal, eh?" Breck sneered. "You want to make a deal when you're cornered? What's the game?" He turned to his companion. "What do you think?"\par
"Sure," the other replied. "What have we got to lose?"\par
"Okay. Shoot," Breck said to the boys.\par
"Tell us, then," Frank asked, "what are you really after?"\par
"Very simple," Breck replied. "I'm only helping Mr. York here regain his rightful inheritance."\par
"What inheritance do you mean?" Joe spoke up.\par
"This land belongs to him."\par
"And what's more, we don't intend to let Chief Whitestone produce any papers to disprove it," York chimed in.\par
"We were getting along fine until you young meddlers came into the picture," Breck went on. "You almost ruined things for us, but now we've got you and your fat friend too."\par
"Chet Morton's been captured?" Frank cried.\par
"Yeah."\par
Joe moved forward. He wanted to choke this ruthless scoundrel. But Frank held him back.\par
"We warned you to lay off," Breck sneered. "But you didn't pay any attention. Thought you were smart detectives, but look where it got you."\par
The boys remained silent, seething as Breck recounted the story of the plot to deprive the Ramapans of their land.\par
"Now, you've come to the end of the line," Breck said, his voice becoming cold as steel. "You and your father."\par
"Where's Dad?" Frank cried.\par
"That you won't find out. And now how about your end of the bargain? Where's the treasure hidden?"\par
When the boys did not answer at once, he cried, "Come on! It's almost daybreak and we've got to clear out of here before it gets light!"\par
Joe looked at Frank, who was clenching his fists.\par
"You want the treasure, eh?" the older boy parried.\par
"Hurry up!"\par
"Walk along this ledge. You'll find a slab o\'a3 rock sticking out. Turn in there and keep going. Feel around for more sharp-pointed rocks and start counting. When you get to the twelfth one, reach up."\par
Joe could hardly keep his face straight. How plausible Frank's story sounded!\par
The two men in their eagerness forgot to be cautious. While they followed directions, arguing all the way, the boys waited till they were out of earshot before speaking.\par
In a moment they were far enough away. Frank whispered to Joe, "The rope! Let's use it now!"\par
Swiftly and silently the boys jumped to the other ledge. They grasped the rope, and reeling it as they climbed, worked their way to the top of the cliff.\par
Suddenly there came a shout of anger from below. "Hey, you double-crossers, come back!"\par
As the boys scrambled to the top, Breck and York yelled curses from below.\par
"We've made it!" Joe exclaimed, throwing his leg over the top of the cliff and dragging himself up. Frank quickly followed.\par
"You have, eh?" a voice cried out.\par
They looked up. Three strange men, obviously armed, had them ambushed!\par
"If you value your lives, don't run!" one yelled.\par
The unequal struggle lasted only a minute. The boys were once more prisoners. Getting a close look at one of the trio, Joe whispered to Frank:\par
"Look at the one in the Indian suit! He's the man I shadowed that day I was attacked by Smirkis!"\par
"Shut up!" the man ordered.\par
A second one said, "You guys have given us a lot of trouble. We ought to drop you over the cliff. What say, gang?"\par
Meanwhile, the rope which was tied around a tree had been let down. At that moment Breck and York appeared at the rim. It was daybreak now and in the light the boys could see their angry faces plainly.\par
"You lied about the treasure!" Breck yelled. "We don't go for things like that! Come on, York! We'll show them!"\par
He grasped Frank by the shoulder while York grabbed Joe. With the others helping, the boys were slowly but surely pushed toward the edge of the cliff!\par
\par
